<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chuck Norris, the tough-guy hero of such
movies as ``Good Guys Wear Black'' and ``Delta Force,'' wore a dark
suit for the unveiling of his Hollywood Walk of Fame star.
   About 200 people gathered for Friday's ceremony on Hollywood
Boulevard near the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, where star No. 1,905
bears Norris' name.
   ``I really didn't expect this kind of a turnout,'' said Norris,
who was accompanied by his wife, two sons and mother. ``I'll always
remember this day.''
   President Bush wrote a letter to the action-film icon, known as
a staunch Republican, which read: ``It's in concrete now: You are a
star. But we all knew that.''
   Originally a martial arts teacher, Norris went into acting on
the recommendation of Steve McQueen, who was one of his students.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Brigitte Nielsen, the strapping star
of ``Red Sonja'' and other action films, gave birth to a healthy
youngster and both were doing fine, a spokesman said.
   Marcus Gastineau, 7 pounds, 11 ounces, was born at 2 a.m. Friday
in an undisclosed Scottsdale, Ariz., hospital, said publicist Joel
Brokaw.
   The 26-year-old actress co-starred in ``Beverly Hills Cop II''
and appeared with ex-husband Sylvester Stallone in the films
``Cobra'' and ``Rocky IV.''
   Miss Nielsen lives in Arizona with Mark Gastineau, who is
awaiting a final divorce decree from his wife, Lisa. Gastineau, an
All-Pro defensive end in the New York Jets' ``sack exchange,'' quit
football during the 1988 season.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roseanne Barr, TV's caustic comedy mom,
called off her January wedding and announced her boyfriend was in a
drug rehabilitation clinic.
   ``My January 20 marriage to Tom Arnold is off,'' Miss Barr said.
   The terse statement Friday was the only comment from the star of
TV's ``Roseanne,'' and the movie ``She-Devil,'' said her publicist,
Lisa Kasteler. The name and location of the rehabilitation clinic
was confidential and the type of addiction wasn't disclosed.
   The temperamental Miss Barr, 36, recently protested the firing
of Arnold, a writer and comic, as a consultant to the show.
   During taping of ``A Current Affair'' TV segment in August,
Arnold dropped his pants and exposed a backside tattoo reading,
``Rosey.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crooner Julio Iglesias has sold 150 million
records worldwide and makes $22 million a year, but something's
lacking: to become one of America's greatest idols.
   ``America has only five great stars, and all except one are
dead: Elvis, Marilyn Monroe, John Kennedy, James Dean and Frank
Sinatra,'' Iglesias says in the January issue of Vanity Fair.
   The first step toward joining their ranks has been for Iglesias,
46, to learn the language. In his efforts to become fluent in
English, Iglesias has worked with a Hollywood speech coach for the
past six years.
   The result? ``Now I understand the news and jokes on Saturday
Night Live,'' said Iglesias, who has recorded duets with Willie
Nelson and Diana Ross.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of sending threatening
letters to actor Michael J. Fox pleaded guilty to three felony
counts and was placed on probation for three years.
   The surprise plea bargain by Tina Marie Ledbetter, 27, was
entered Friday. In exchange for the three guilty pleas, prosecutors
dropped two counts. She could have been sentenced to four years in
prison if found guilty of all charges.
   The 28-year-old California woman allegedly sent nearly 6,000
threatening letters to the ``Family Ties'' star over the course of
a year, with 800 of them arriving in July 1988, the month he
married actress Tracy Pollan.
   ``Divorce Tracy or you are dead!'' one letter said. ``I am
coming after you with a gun and I'm going to kill you if you don't
divorce Tracy immediately.''
   Fox, 28, whose movie roles include ``Back to the Future'' and
``Bright Lights, Big City,'' was unavailable for comment, said his
publicist, Nancy Ryder.
</TEXT>
