<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 0042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MedalDenied Bjt   12-16 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medal Denied, Bjt,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Says It Couldn't Back Medal of Honor Contender's Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army says it won't give the Medal of Honor
to a Wisconsin man because it could not prove his claims that he
single-handedly killed more than 500 Japanese soldiers during World
War II.
   Congressional leaders, who pushed for the investigation into the
claims by David S. Rubitsky, accepted the findings Friday and said
they found the probe ``fair, thorough and conclusive.''
   Lt. Col. Terry Adkins told reporters the Army could not even
prove fierce fighting occurred Dec. 1-2, 1942, as claimed by
Rubitsky, now 72.
   The Milton, Wis., man contends he was denied the medal because
he is Jewish.
   ``I could not find any basis of this,'' Adkins, chief of the
Army's Military Awards Branch, said of the anti-Semitism charge by
Rubitsky. ``I just don't have the information to prove it.''
   At his home, Rubitsky said he had not been formally notified of
the board's ruling. ``I'm not going to make a statement until I'm
damn sure what the facts are myself,'' he said.
   ``We're very disappointed but we're not giving up yet,'' his
wife, Katherine Roethe, said.
   Adkins said the decision not to award the medal came after the
Army examined scores of documents, including testimony from
Japanese prisoners of war, battle logs and interviews.
   The officer told Congress of the Army's findings earlier Friday,
and four lawmakers quickly issued a statement saying: ``The
investigation established as conclusively as possible after half a
century that there was no mass killing of Japanese attackers at
Buna in New Guinea in 1942.''
   The statement was issued from Reps. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman
of the House Armed Services Committee, and Nita M. Lowey, D-N.Y.,
and Sens. Robert W. Kasten Jr., R-Wis., and Herbert H. Kohl, D-Wis.
   ``What we are dealing with here is not a lie fabricated by the
generals and Mr. Rubitsky. It is simply the unfortunate result of
the passage of many years, the fogging of many memories and the
reliving of many difficult memories from a war long past,'' the
statement said.
   Rubitsky said he killed up to 600 Japanese soldiers in the New
Guinea jungles during a 21-hour siege. According to Adkins,
Rubitsky said he believed his action saved his battalion from
imminent attack and he killed wounded enemy soldiers with a bayonet
and pistol.
   Adkins, noting the latter claim would have been against the
Geneva War Convention, said his studies showed there were about
1,000 American troops and 500 Japanese soldiers in the area called
Buna and the Japanese were in a defensive rather than offensive
stance.
   Rubitsky said there was fighting through the night, but
battalion logs indicated it was quiet. Tours by officers indicated
little activity. In fact, Adkins said, the company commander was
relieved for failing to follow Gen. Douglas McArthur's order of:
``Take Buna or don't come back alive.''
   Japanese records likewise don't support the contention that
intense combat occurred, Adkins said.
   Joseph Stehling, a retired brigadier general, signed an
affidavit outlining Rubitsky's actions and saying he nominated
Rubitsky for the Medal of Honor. Retired Gen. Herbert Smith, who
died in September, signed a similar affidavit.
   Another affidavit in the case, signed by a military messenger,
said a colonel, now dead, had denied Rubitsky his medal because
Rubitsky was Jewish.
   In a 1988 interview, Rubitsky said he had received numerous
anti-Semitic phone calls and threats after deciding to fight for
the medal.
</TEXT>
