<FIRST>u w AM-Military-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0406 12-16 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0406,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Moving Ahead With Plans For Drug War</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Replaces 4th graf pvs with 3 grafs with more info; picks up
5th graf pvs, The Marine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon soon will approve plans submitted
by 10 commanders for increased activities in the war on drugs, a
spokesman said Friday.
   Defense Secretary Richard Cheney received the reports Oct. 15 on
``how their commands could become more involved in the support to
counter-narcotics missions,'' said Maj. David Super. ``We can't
talk about any of the specific recommendations.''
   Military sources said, however, that future plans included more
use of AWACS surveillance and control aircraft to detect planes
carrying drugs, air deployable ground-based radar systems, naval
combat ships and fixed and mobile sensors.
   One Marine Corps reconnaissance team helping the Border Patrol
in Arizona exchanged gunfire with marijuana smugglers on horseback
Wednesday night, officials said Friday.
   No one was injured in the Wednesday night firefight which
members of the U.S. group estimated at 30 minutes in duration.
After the alleged smugglers fled on horseback, Marines and Border
Patrol agents, who were on foot, confiscated about 570 pounds of
marijuana.
   The incident marked the first direct conflict involving Marines
since they began accompanying the Border Patrol about two weeks ago.
   The Marines Corps referred questions to the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, which did not immediately respond.
   The military's role under Cheney is markedly different from his
predecessor, Frank Carlucci. Whereas Cheney describes the
military's participation as ``crucial,'' Carlucci said in June 1988
he was ``absolutely opposed to the assignment of a law enforcement
mission to the Department of Defense.''
   Meanwhile, officials declined to comment on a report by CBS News
that the Pentagon had authorized plans by military units to capture
fugitive drug criminals in foreign countries.
   The Washington Post said in Saturday editions that a Justice
Department memo of Nov. 3 concludes that the federal law forbidding
use of the military as police officers does not apply outside the
boundaries of the United States.
   The Defense Department's larger role in counter-narcotics began
last year with a congressional appropriation of $300 million. That
figure was upped to $450 million this year.
   Congress assigned the Pentagon to be the lead and coordinating
agency for detecting and monitoring aerial and maritime drug
smuggling, creating a network for the intelligence community and
increasing the work of the National Guard.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Friday that Air Force analysts
have suggested the service use high-resolution spy satellites to
provide glimpses of shifting ground bases for drug traffickers,
including their jungle laboratories.
   It said Navy budget planners recommended shifting some Atlantic
training operations to the Caribbean, where sailors could keep
watch on drug trafficking from international waters off Colombia.
   ``With peace breaking out all over, it might give us something
to do,'' the newspaper quoted an unidentified two-star general as
saying.
   Cheney last month approved the formation of a new anti-drug task
force at Fort Bliss, Texas. The new group, Joint Task Force 6, is
to deal with drug activity along the southern border. It joined two
other task forces set up earlier this year to stem the flow of
drugs.
   The one at Oakland, Calif., ``detects and monitors aircraft and
surface vessels suspected of smuggling illegal drugs into the
United States from the Pacific,'' a statement said. The one in Key
West, Fla., conducts counter-narcotics work in the Caribbean.
   In its report Thursday night, CBS News said one unit authorized
to capture drug fugitives abroad was the Army's Delta Force hostage
rescue team.
   The report said the U.S. military became involved after an
informant told the U.S. government last summer that Pablo Escobar,
one of the kingpins of the Colombian drug trade, was hiding at a
seaside villa in Panama.
   Troops and helicopters were moved to a U.S. base in Puerto Rico
to prepare for an attempted capture Labor Day weekend, but the plan
was aborted out of suspicion the informant was incorrect. It turned
out Escobar was not in Panama that weekend, CBS said.
   U.S. News &amp; World Report magazine published a similar account of
the Escobar plan in last week's issue.
</TEXT>
