<FIRST>r a PM-MonoLake Bjt   12-16 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mono Lake, Bjt,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Environmentalists See Victory In Fight Over Mono Lake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEE VINING, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel Taylor still remembers the
warning a water department official gave him when environmentalists
began a series of David-and-Goliath court battles with Los Angeles
over scenic Mono Lake.
   ``It's good that you're young,'' the official said, ``because
you'll be old when it's resolved.''
   Those environmentalists have reached or are approaching middle
age, but thanks to a series of favorable court decisions, they have
victory in sight, says Taylor, western regional representative for
the Audubon Society.
   What once seemed a quixotic struggle to save a woebegone lake
has gained the backing of court rulings and legislative action in
recent years as Southern Californians began to come to grip with
environmental concerns over their water and air.
   ``The original question was will we win. Now it's a question of
when will we win,'' said Taylor, 38, who became involved in the
case in the late 1970s. ``It's clear that Mono Lake will not die.''
   Mono was formed a million years ago in a volcanic area just east
of what is now Yosemite National Park, about 260 miles north of Los
Angeles and due east of San Francisco.
   The lake, which in its heyday covered about 80 square miles, is
best known for its high salt level and oddly shaped limestone
formations _ tufa _ that stand cactuslike along part of its shore.
   Mark Twain called the place ``the Dead Sea of the West.''
Naturalist John Muir saw it as a ``country of wonderful contrasts:
Hot deserts bounded by snow-laden mountains ... frost and fire
working together in the making of beauty.''
   Congress created a national forest scenic area at the lake in
1984.
   But Mono has been shrinking since Los Angeles began diverting
water in 1941 using an aqueduct system to tap tributary streams.
   The diversions have dropped the lake's level about 40 feet and
reduced its size to about 60 square miles. Environmentalists say
that if the trend continues the lake will be turned into an
``alkali wasteland'' unable to support Mono's brine shrimp or
various birds.
   But recent court rulings and legislation indicate the
environmentalists may be able to claim victory.
   ``There have been very important developments that signal that
it really is a question of how soon, rather than whether, Mono Lake
will be protected,'' said Martha Davis, executive director of the
Mono Lake Committee, an environmental group created in 1978 that
now has 20,000 dues-paying members.
   ``There's also much more work ahead of us to really translate
some of the legal and political victories of this year into
permanent protection for the lake.''
   Duane Georgeson, assistant general manager of the Los Angeles
Department of Water and Power, says it's ``a little early for
anyone to claim a victory unless you're interested only in counting
court orders.''
   But he says the city recognizes ``that at some point there will
have to be some reductions in our diversions.''
   Environmentalists won a major victory in 1983, when the state
Supreme Court ruled that water uses could be altered to protect the
``public trust.''
   They scored this year when state courts said that Los Angeles'
licenses to export water from the Mono Lake Basin must be revised
to require the city to release fish-sustaining flows in four
streams that feed the lake.
   Also this year, a Superior Court judge issued a preliminary
injunction that, in effect, forced the city to stop taking water
from the basin. The injunction remains in force through March, and
environmentalists say they will seek to extend it.
   The Legislature, with backing from environmentalists and Los
Angeles, voted this year to create a $60 million fund to find ways
to replace water the city takes from the Mono Basin.
   The author of one of the bills, Democratic Assemblyman Phil
Isenberg, said the city-environmental group support for the
legislation signaled ``the beginning of the end to an acrimonious
50-year water war.''
   ``Los Angeles has seen the handwriting on the wall,'' he said.
``Psychologically, this is a new LA. ... These are folks who don't
like to be portrayed as rapers of the environment. They would like
to get out from under it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
