<FIRST>r w PM-Congressmen-Colombia     12-16 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressmen-Colombia,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Say Colombian Anti-Drug Fight is Courageous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressmen back from a secret trip to
Colombia say they are more convinced than ever that President
Virgilio Barco deserves unwavering support in his country's bloody
battle with drug traffickers.
   ``The Colombian people are inspiring, courageous,'' Rep. Frank
Guarini, D-N.J., said Friday on returning from the South American
nation. ``We will stand with them.''
   Guarini and five colleagues on the House Select Committee on
Narcotics Abuse and Control, led by Chairman Charles Rangel,
D-N.Y., said they saw firsthand a nation trying to resist
intimidation by a handful of powerful drug kingpins.
   Since Barco announced the anti-drug initiative three months ago,
Colombia has seen 50 judges, two newspaper publishers, the chief of
the narcotics police and a leading presidential candidate slain.
   Colombia got a fresh dose of violence Friday when police killed
Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, one of the most powerful cocaine barons,
in a shootout near the port city of Covenas.
   Rodriguez Gacha, his 17-year-old son Fredy and five bodyguards
were slain in a gun battle on a ranch owned by Pablo Escobar,
godfather of Colombia's multibillion-dollar drug empire, Colombian
authorities said.
   At a news conference at Andrews Air Force Base, the lawmakers
praised Barco for his courage in the face of bombings and
assassinations that have chipped away at that nation's government.
   ``You have to be there to understand the kind of fear that we
saw,'' said Rep. William Hughes, D-N.J.
   They visited the site of last week's deadly bomb blast that
destroyed the Colombian Intelligence and Security Directorate, and
lawmakers visited a hospital where victims are recuperating.
   All agreed that despite death threats against top Colombian
officials, President Bush should attend a planned Feb. 15 drug
summit in the Colombian city of Cartagena to demonstrate U.S.
support for Barco's war against drug lords.
   Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, R-N.Y., called the Bush visit ``a
strong symbolic gesture'' that would improve Colombian morale.
   ``We will collect our forces in the Congress to provide the type
of resources that will be necessary to make this war victorious,''
said Rangel.
   Hughes said he assured Barco the United States would assist
Colombia by restricting the flow of U.S.-made assault weapons and
cocaine processing chemicals to South America, limiting
money-laundering activities in the United States and providing
greater protection for witnesses willing to testify against drug
lords.
   Aides kept the two-day trip secret because of concerns the
congressmen could become the targets of cocaine traffickers.
</TEXT>
