<FIRST>r a PM-Escapees'Suit     12-16 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Escapees' Suit,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Inmates Sue Missouri, Say Escape Was For Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two inmates said they broke out of prison
because life there was so dangerous they had no other choice to
protect themselves, and are suing the state for $1.8 million.
   In the damage suit filed in federal court this week, Jimmie
Perko and Neil Sleeper complained of widespread violence and lax
security inside the medium-security state prison at Moberly in
central Missouri, which they escaped Sept. 5. They were recaptured
two days later.
   ``A person can only put up with this constant fear for so long
until he is forced to seek safety; in this case it was to escape
the situation,'' the inmates said in the lawsuit.
   Perko, 28, is serving a 15-year sentence for robbery and other
charges. Sleeper, 31, is serving a 10-year term for first-degree
assault.
   They stated further that guards had failed to detect them
``tearing the window out of their cell'' and thus failed their duty
to keep the public safe from convicted felons.
   J.M. Jones, the prison superintendent, said Friday that both men
had been transferred to the Missouri Penitentiary in Jefferson
City. He said he was unaware of the lawsuit and declined to discuss
it.
</TEXT>
