<FIRST>r w PM-LaborBudget     12-16 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Labor Budget,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Department Wins Two Budget Battles for '91, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will increase spending
in fiscal 1991 for Labor Department job training programs and for
enforcement of pension and worker-safety laws.
   The increases will be included in the budget request the White
House sends Congress on Jan. 22 for the fiscal year that begins
next Oct. 1, sources told The Associated Press on Friday.
   The Labor Department lost in a bid for a major funding boost for
a program designed to help dislocated workers but welcomed the
overall spending and will not appeal the Office of Management and
Budget decisions to President Bush, said administration officials
who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   The sources said the bottom line for the Labor Department budget
could change if some other major departments, the Defense
Department among them, win their appeals to the president for
funding above the levels decided by the budget office. That would
cause budget planners to look at other departments to recoup funds.
   The spending agreement for the Labor Department includes planned
funding boosts for the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration and the Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration.
   The figures are what the administration plans to request in
budget authority; actual appropriations are determined after
Congress adopts spending limits.
   The Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration oversees the
nation's nearly $2 trillion private pension system and has been
criticized by the department's inspector general, who says the
system is ripe for fraud because of inadequate oversight and
incomplete auditing of pension funds.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole asked for a more than $6 million
spending boost for the pension agency, according to the sources.
   They said the budget office accepted a figure ``very close'' to
the department's request and that as a result the agency would be
able to hire 100 additional enforcement workers in fiscal 1991.
   The department requested $15.7 million in additional funding for
the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, which has a
budget authorization of $270 million for the current year. Again,
the sources declined to provide the amount approved by the budget
office but said it was ``essentially what we asked for'' and would
allow for the hiring of an undetermined number of new inspectors
and other enforcement personnel.
   Also included in department's agreement with the budget office
is $250 million in additional money for the Job Training
Partnership Act, which has a budget of about $1.7 billion this year.
   All of the new money would fund a package of job training
amendments pending before Congress and endorsed by Bush earlier
this year. Those changes are expected to be passed early next year.
</TEXT>
