<FIRST>r w PM-LegalServices     12-16 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Legal Services,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Keeps Embattled Conservative President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrance Wear will remain as the president of
the federal Legal Services Corp. after surviving a vote for his
ouster pushed by liberal members of the agency's board of directors.
   Former Rep. John Erlenborn, R-Ill., named to the panel by
President Bush last month, cast the deciding vote Friday against a
motion to dismiss Wear after a day-long meeting in which the
conservative president's performance was examined.
   The 11-member panel discussed Wear's use of outside counsel and
lobbying of the White House in connection with nominations for the
board. The panel also questioned Wear's hiring and payment of the
agency's inspector general without prior board approval.
   Erlenborn and Texas attorney J. Blakely Hall, who had previously
served on the board, were appointed during the year-end recess of
Congress, thus avoiding Senate confirmation.
   Friday's meeting was the latest in a continuing battle between
two factions on the board, which oversees the independent agency
that offers legal help to the nation's poor.
   The agency has been the subject of controversy since 1981, when
conservatives targeted it for abolishment.
   Now those conservatives, buttressed by Wear, want to limit the
agency's field attorneys' activities in class-action lawsuits
against the government over welfare and other social programs,
according to Carolyn Stewart of the National Legal Aid and
Defenders Association.
   Conservatives held a 6-5 majority on the board until two
vacancies recently occurred, according to Terry Roach, an
independent consultant and longtime LSC observer.
   The balance briefly tipped to a 5-4 majority in favor of the
broader range of activities, and one board member, Thomas Smegal,
unsuccessfully tried to oust Wear.
</TEXT>
