<FIRST>r a PM-Eco-Terrorists Bjt   12-16 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eco-Terrorists, Bjt,0685</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Western Ranchers Worried About ``Environmental Terrorists'' ^By
ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Range wars are nothing new to ranchers, but
hit-and-run vandalism that the FBI blames on environmental
terrorists is igniting new conflict in the West.
   ``It's a case of ecological terrorism,'' FBI agent Richard
Whitaker said of a growing number of incidents, including
castration of cattle, sabotage of farm machinery, freeing of farm
animals and possibly death threats against a rancher and a
government animal manager.
   ``Their basic goal is to eradicate the rancher,'' Whitaker said.
   The attacks have become more prevalent in Nevada, California and
Arizona in recent months. Some ranchers say damage they previously
thought was the work of pranksters or hunters may be a concerted
effort by animal rights activists and environmental groups.
   ``These things are terrorist activities,'' says Jim Connelley,
president of the Nevada Cattlemen's Association. ``These people
have total disregard for the law. They are criminal and terrorist
in nature.''
   Animal rights and environmental groups such as Animal Liberation
Front and Earth First! have been accused of the hit-and-run
attacks, which have been stepped up in the last 18 months, Whitaker
said in a recent interview here.
   The Animal Liberation Front _ best known for freeing research
animals and vandalizing laboratories _ is seeking ``the elimination
of the livestock industry,'' spokeswoman Margo Tannenbaum said.
   ``The reason why the Animal Liberation Front is conducting
economic sabotage to the poultry and livestock industries is to
encourage those involved to quit and follow other pursuits,'' she
said.
   Earth First! adherents may be responsible for some of the acts,
said spokesman Lynn Jacobs in Tucson. But Jacobs denied knowledge
of specific attacks by followers of the militant environmental
group.
   ``I don't advocate that anyone break the law unless they feel
it's the right thing to do,'' Jacobs said.
   The FBI's Whitaker said any livestock operator is a potential
target for militant vegetarians who shun meat, dairy products, eggs
or cheese, refuse to wear leather or wool and think others should
follow suit.
   Among the incidents in Nevada, according to cattleman Connelley,
are castration of bulls kept for breeding, cutting of fences and
water pipelines, toppling of troughs and water tanks and damage to
windmills and wells.
   Pam Neal, executive vice president of the Arizona Cattlemen's
Association in Phoenix, said she received a death threat on her
telephone answering machine a week after she testified at a
congressional hearing in favor of multiple uses of public land. She
blames the threat on ecological terrorists.
   Darrell Juve, the Arizona director of a U.S. Agriculture
Department program to kill predators and diseased animals, said he
also received a death threat, and later a military ``practice''
grenade was tossed into offices near his.
   Ranchers want Congress and state legislatures to make it a
felony to disrupt food production in any way.
   ``My assessment is that they're totally misguided, they don't
have the foggiest idea of the benefits of the livestock industry,''
Connelley said of the activists. ``We are the original ecologists.
We're the ones who originally came West, took it on ourselves to
produce something from nothing. We are dependent on the ecology.
   ``Some of these people are cooped up in an apartment in the big
city and the closest they ever get to nature is a Sunset magazine.
They tend to get a little misguided.''
   Animal Liberation Front members prefer releasing animals to
damaging equipment, Ms. Tannenbaum said. Each year they try to raid
turkey farms before Thanksgiving and rabbit farms before Easter.
   Front activists released 300 wild horses from a federal Bureau
of Land Management lot in northern California and beef cattle from
a feedlot in Coalinga, Calif. last year, she said.
   The group also claimed responsibility for freeing more than 600
partridges in May from pens belonging to Chukars Unlimited, a
hunters' group near Elko, Nev., that keeps the birds to be shot.
Many of the released birds were killed by vehicles on a nearby
highway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891216-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 0149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-LookingGlass     12-16 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Looking Glass,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nixes Proposal to Ground Airborne Command Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will keep the airborne command
post that flies continuously in case of nuclear attack despite a
Pentagon recommendation that the flights be grounded part of the
time.
   An administration official, who disclosed Bush's decision to The
Associated Press on condition he not be identified, said the
president and national security adviser Brent Scowcroft discussed
the matter after word of the Pentagon's plans appeared in Friday
editions of The New York Times.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney telegraphed the decision earlier
Friday, telling reporters, ``I don't believe we'll go forward with
it. ... I think we'll continue to fly it as we have in the past.''
   They decided that to end the flights would send ``the wrong
signal at this time, that we may be cutting back in military
capability,'' the official said.
   The administration's plans to seek lower defense budgets have
been known for weeks.
   A decreased Soviet threat and the prospect of saving $20 million
a year were cited as support for the proposal to ground the command
post, known as ``Looking Glass.''
   The post carries a general of the Strategic Air Command and
supporting staff to issue battle orders in case of a nuclear war
that kills or disables the president and other command authorities.
   The Looking Glass planes have been flying since 1961. The Air
Force proposed that they fly only part of the time, with the
general and his staff on ground alert the rest of the time.
   The planes fly from Offutt Air Force Base in Nebraska.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
