<FIRST>r a PM-BorderShootout     12-16 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Border Shootout,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marines, Drug Smugglers Exchange Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOGALES, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines working with U.S. Border Patrol
agents exchanged gunfire with a group of drug smugglers on
horseback in the first battle between troops and smugglers since
the military began border patrols, officials said.
   The Marines did not shoot to kill, and no one was injured in the
half-hour fight Wednesday night outside this border city, officials
said Friday.
   The Marines were part of a 50-soldier contingent who have been
assisting Border Patrol agents, primarily in surveillance, since
the program started two weeks ago, Lt. Col. Ron Stokes said from
Marine headquarters in Washington.
   The contingent was on its way to an observation point about
three miles from Nogales when the horsemen were spotted, Stokes
said.
   The Border Patrol agent ordered the Marines to fire a flare to
light up the area, Stokes said. With the ground lighted, the men on
horseback began shooting at the Marines.
   The Marines, armed with M-16 assault rifles, returned the
volley, firing over the heads of smugglers ``in order to try to
scare their horses,'' Stokes said.
   After the riders fled, Marines and Border Patrol agents
confiscated about 570 pounds of marijuana.
   Bob Maynes, a spokesman for Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said
the firefight underlined the reasons why federal troops should be
involved against drug smugglers.
   ``The willingness of drug smugglers to fire across an
international border when no shots had been fired at them is a
clear indication of the dangerous kind of individuals we're dealing
with,'' Maynes said.
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, which directs
the Border Patrol, announced in October that it planned to use
Marines to aid in drug interdiction.
   At the time, Hispanic rights groups voiced concerns that Marines
on the border would prompt increased violence and human rights
abuses because Marines are not trained in civilian law enforcement.
   The Mexican government also raised concerns.
   The Marines do not have the authority to arrest people or
conduct searches and seizures, Stokes said.
   Local police said they were not notified of the gunfight.
   Capt. Tony Estrada of the Nogales, Ariz., police said the
confrontation was ``news to me until I received a call from a
reporter.''
   Both city police and the sheriff's department are normally
notified by federal officials when shootings take place in their
areas.
</TEXT>
