<FIRST>r a PM-Attorney-Bombing     12-16 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Attorney-Bombing,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Attorney Seriously Wounded in Car Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb severely injured a well-known criminal
attorney with a lengthy list of clients including drug dealers and
rightist Cuban militants.
   Gino P. Negretti, 71, pushed himself out of his wrecked car and
was aided by neighbors who rushed to help when his late-model
Cadillac exploded shortly after he started it Friday morning.
   Negretti narrowly escaped flames that engulfed the car after the
blast in a residential section of Miami, police spokesman David
Rivero said.
   Investigators have begun checking Negretti's client list, Rivero
said.
   ``He's pretty well known as a defense attorney, and a lot of his
clients are drug defendants,'' said Rivero. ``Obviously, that's one
of the angles that will be checked. Maybe he had a problem with one
of his clients.''
   Neighbor Juan Cardenas said the explosion was ``very, very
loud.''
   ``That's why I ran outside,'' he said. ``Then we saw the flames
and smoke. He's a fortunate man.''
   Negretti was rushed into surgery at Jackson Memorial Hospital,
where doctors removed shrapnel from his arms and legs, Rivero said.
Both of Negretti's arms were broken but none of his vital organs
appeared to have been hit, he said.
   The Puerto Rican-born attorney has been well known in Miami
legal circles for decades, repesenting defendants in prominent
cases involving the city's Cuban-American community.
   Negretti defended anti-Castro activist Humberto Lopez Jr., who
fled to the Dominican Republic while appealing a conviction for
illegal possession of explosives.
   He was one of the attorneys who in 1967 represented six men
convicted of an attempted invasion of part of Haiti in a plan to
set up a base for launching anti-Castro actions against Cuba.
</TEXT>
