<FIRST>r a PM-NAACPAnniversary     12-16 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP Anniversary,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Cancels, Snow Fizzles But NAACP Party Went On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAUL REYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP was expecting President Bush and snow.
Neither arrived, but the organization's 80th anniversary party went
on anyway.
   Bush's arrival for the Friday night fete was viewed with
trepidation by some city officials who said it and forecast snow
would create gridlock on streets mobbed with holiday shoppers.
   Bush got a case of laryngitis and stayed in Washington, but put
in an appearance through a long-distance hook-up with the audience
at the Waldorf-Astoria.
   He said he wanted the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People to work with his administration in combatting
drugs, improving educational opportunities and helping the homeless.
   During his brief telephone remarks, Bush repeatedly apologized
for not attending the $500-a-person dinner.
   ``Even our dog thinks I look sick as a dog,'' he said to laughs.
   Bush promised to ``use my office to speak out against racism and
bigotry wherever it is found as long as I am president of the
United States.''
   Benjamin Hooks, NAACP executive director, said the president's
absence should not be misconstrued.
   ``He is a man who is trying to lead us to become a gentler,
kinder nation,'' Hooks said. ``I want you to know the NCAAP stands
ready to achieve that goal and purpose.''
   Secretary of Health and Human Services Louis Sullivan stepped in
for Bush at the last minute and quoted from portions of Bush's
prepared speech, urging the NAACP to join forces with the Bush
administration.
   Prominent officials attending the event included David Dinkins,
the first black elected mayor of New York, and Virginia Gov.-elect
L. Douglas Wilder, who last month became the first elected black
governor in the nation.
</TEXT>
