<FIRST>r a PM-Boesky     12-16 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boesky,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boesky To Finish Sentence At Brooklyn Halfway House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ivan F. Boesky, Wall Street's most famous felon,
has been released from a federal prison camp and will serve the
rest of his sentence at a halfway house, authorities said.
   Boesky, 52, was granted a transfer to the house about 10 days
ago from the minimum-security Lompoc Federal Prison Camp in
California, where he had been imprisoned since March 1988, prison
spokesman Gavin O'Connor said Friday.
   Boesky actually has been out of the Lompoc prison since early
November, when he received a monthlong furlough for good behavior.
During his time out, Boesky became eligible for a transfer to the
less-restrictive halfway house.
   The former Wall Street stock speculator was photographed by the
New York Post last month in Stamford, Conn., wearing
shoulder-length gray hair and a long, scraggly beard. He was
spotted in New York City last week wearing a business suit, with
his hair and beard neatly trimmed.
   ``He fulfills the requirement for release at the halfway
house,'' O'Connor said. ``That's the regular procedure.''
   At his new quarters, Boesky has an evening curfew and must
arrange his activities through supervisors.
   Leon Silverman, one of Boesky's attorneys, confirmed that Boesky
had been released to the halfway house but declined further comment.
   In November 1986, Boesky paid $100 million to the Securities and
Exchange Commission and agreed to plead guilty to one criminal
count to settle charges related to a large insider-trading network.
   He was sentenced to three years in prison and is eligible for
release on good behavior next April after completing two-thirds of
his term.
   Boesky is cooperating with the government and is expected to
testify against former junk bond financier Michael Milken, whose
trial is set for next year.
   At Lompoc, Boesky generally worked on a prison cleanup crew that
took care of the visitor areas. He was paid 11 cents an hour for
his labor.
   ``He's a nice man, to be perfectly honest,'' O'Connor said. ``He
was a good man to have around. A good man to speak to. Always
pleasant.''
   Boesky is renovating his home on a 75-acre estate north of New
York City. The building permit for the work puts the estimated cost
of the project at about $1.22 million.
   A group of local union workers has picketed the building for two
weeks to protest non-union work being done on the mansion.
</TEXT>
