<FIRST>r a PM-HollywoodAuction     12-16 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hollywood Auction,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monroe Gown, Monster Mask Big Sellers at Auction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Carrousel in 9th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A siren-red, sequin-encrusted evening gown that
gentlemen preferred to see Marilyn Monroe wearing fetched $14,300
at an auction of Hollywood memorabilia.
   The dress worn in ``Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' was sold Friday
to an unidentified buyer at Sotheby's auction house. The
unidentified seller also threw in a Life magazine cover showing
Miss Monroe in the gown and Jane Russell in an identical one.
   A white lace bustier, which Miss Monroe wore under a different
gown in the 1960 movie ``Let's Make Love,'' went for $1,430. And a
black bra, of unspecified origin but inscribed with the sex
symbol's name, sold for $605.
   The beauty got some competition from a beast: a rubber monster
head from the 1954 movie, ``The Creature of the Black Lagoon.'' A
Canadian private collector got it for $5,610 _ well above the
pre-sale estimate of $2,000 to $3,000.
   The monster mask, in fetching sea green with red lips, is
highlighted by ``many gills to the back'' and large moles, the
auction catalog notes. When not being worn, it can be displayed in
its own clear case.
   A Salvador Dali backdrop from Alfred Hitchcock's ``Spellbound,''
valued at $60,000 to $80,000, was bought back when it failed to
make the undisclosed minimum. So was a navy blue and white checked,
cotton pinafore worn by Judy Garland in the ``Wizard of Oz,'' which
the auctioneers had hoped would go for $20,000 to $25,000.
   But an anonymous buyer paid $6,600 for a leather chariot toga
worn by Charlton Heston in ``Ben Hur,'' circa 1959. Brown leather
forearm covers and a blue, 9-foot cape complete the macho ensemble.
   And W.C. Fields's top hat from the 1939 movie, ``My Little
Chickadee,'' went for $3,300 to a private collector _ a bargain,
below the estimate of $4,000 to $6,000.
   The Hollywood mementos were part of Sotheby's annual Collector's
Carrousel sale that also includes toys, dolls, animated art, music
boxes and baseball memorabilia. The sale continued today.
</TEXT>
