<SECOND>PM-Death Squad Arrest,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested in Los Angeles Linked To Salvadoran Death Squads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman arrested for investigation of
making threats against a former employee was linked by police to
death squads in El Salvador, authorities said.
   Carlos Rene Mata, 35, was being held Friday after arraignment on
charges he made a terrorist threat and received stolen property.
   Mata, owner of the Pipil Express international overnight
delivery company, was not charged in connection with death squad
activities.
   An affidavit filed in Municipal Court by police Detective Steve
Spear said ``confidential, reliable'' sources have linked Mata to
the death squads.
   Mata's attorney, Donald C. Randolph, denied his client was
involved in death squads and said he was being victimized by
authorities for his links to the Republican Nationalist Alliance,
the rightist party in power in El Salvador.
   Opponents of the U.S.-supported government in El Salvador have
blamed three Los Angeles kidnappings on Salvadoran death squads. In
the last two years, Catholic churches in the region have received
more than 100 threatening letters and phone calls, police said.
   Mata and a male employee of Pipil Express were ordered in
November to stand trial for the alleged rape of a 24-year-old woman
in the company's Pico-Union district office.
   Last month, Mata pleaded guilty to federal charges he used his
firm to smuggle illegal immigrants into the United States.
   And on Thursday, Mata was arraigned on charges he made a
threatening phone call to a former employee who had cooperated with
authorities investigating the illegal immigrant smuggling.
   He was also charged in connection with two stolen Mercedez-Benz
automobiles found at his home. Bail was set at on $500,000.
</TEXT>
