<FIRST>r a PM-Flight103-Families     12-16 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Families,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Suit May Have to Be Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing national security concerns, a federal
judge refused to release details about the U.S. government's
investigation into the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 for use in a
lawsuit against the airline.
   Judge Thomas C. Platt of U.S. District Court said Friday the
information may have to be withheld until criminal investigations
here and overseas are completed _ which may delay the civil case
for years.
   ``I don't want to be responsible for another airline crash,'' he
said at a hearing.
   Pan Am attorney Anthony A. Dean argued that the case should be
delayed until the court can consider all the evidence about the
bomb, which destroyed Boeing 747 over Lockerbie, Scotland on Dec.
21, killing 259 on the plane and 11 on the ground.
   Lee Kreindler, the lead attorney for relatives of about 150 of
the dead, said it would be unfair to make the families wait that
long for their day in court. The plaintiffs are seeking amounts
ranging from $1 million to $25 million.
   Platt said he felt it might be a waste of time to begin the
trial without the government information, only to have it released
later.
   Pan Am last month subpoenaed six government agencies, including
the FBI and the CIA, seeking documents to use in defending itself
against the civil lawsuits.
   Platt said some of the documents he had reviewed contained
information that he felt might jeopardize American interests.
   He instructed Justice Department lawyer John Connors, who sat in
on the proceedings, to seek guidance from national security
officials in Washington and report back.
   ``I want you to find out if you released what evidence you have
now, without mentioning names, whether they would regard that as
breaching national security,'' Platt said.
   No date was set for Connors to report to Platt.
   Outside the courtroom, Dean said he felt the documents may show
that parties other than Pan Am, possibly even government agencies,
shared responsibility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891216-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 0534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonCrews     12-16 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Crews,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Gets More Than Bargained For in Offer to Buy Out Crews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So many Exxon oil-tanker crew members applied for
a company offer to pay them to quit their jobs that a possible
tanker-crew shortage could occur, a company spokesman said.
   Exxon sought the resignations of 76 licensed officers and 71
unlicensed crew members to make up for a cutback in ships and crew
sizes, but nearly twice the number of unlicensed crew members
applied for the buyout, said spokesman Tom Gillette in Houston.
   The number of officers who signed up for the buyout wasn't
available, he said.
   The company conducted the buy-out by seniority on Nov. 22, when
it named the 147 who would be bought out of their jobs, said John
Hillman, vice president of the Seaman's Union at Exxon.
   But since the buyout, other crew members and officers who were
not named on the list have quit because they are fed up with Exxon
policies, Hillman said.
   Gillette said Exxon may have to delay some of the buyouts since
so many people have quit. He did not say how many had quit.
   About 800 people worked in the company's tanker operation before
the buyout plan started.
   Gillette said he believes people are leaving the company for
other opportunities and because the buyout, offering as much as six
months' pay, was so attractive.
   Exxon has cut the number of tankers it operates, from 20 to 13,
because it curtailed shipments on the route from Alaska to the Gulf
Coast, officials said.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez spilled about 11 million gallons of oil
into Alaska's Prince William Sound on March 24 in the worst oil
spill in the country's history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
