<FIRST>r a PM-Sagansky-CBS     12-16 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sagansky-CBS,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Woos New Programs Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS, in search of a programs chief to lead it
out of the ratings wilderness, has reached agreement with Tri-Star
Pictures president Jeff Sagansky, sources close to the negotiations
say.
   CBS officials declined to comment Friday, and a Sagansky
spokesman would say only, ``there is no announcement yet.'' But an
executive who asked to remain anonymous said there would be a joint
announcement Monday by Columbia Studios, which owns Tri-Star, and
CBS.
   Sagansky would be joining CBS at a time it is facing a third
season as No. 3 in prime-time ratings, and considering schedule
changes for the second half of this season.
   He would replace Kim LeMasters, who resigned two weeks ago as
CBS Entertainment president. LeMasters held the job two years.
Ironically, CBS executives had considered Sagansky before picking
LeMasters.
   CBS last week tried unsuccessfully to lure to its vacant job a
top TV production team, Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner. Their company
makes NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and ABC's ``Roseanne.''
   CBS' agreement with Sagansky, 37, was delayed by extended
negotiations between CBS and Columbia Studios for the release of
Sagansky from his Tri-Star contract, CBS officials have said.
   Sagansky, a former senior NBC programs executive, joined
Tri-Star in 1985, and has been head of Tri-Star Pictures since
March.
   Credited with helping develop such films as ``Steel Magnolias,''
``Tap,'' and the just-released ``Glory,'' he would be responsible
for CBS' entire program schedule.
   He would face large task of restoration in coming months at
once-dominant CBS, which last month suffered the worst ratings it
ever has had in November.
   Although its daytime schedule emerged first in the November
ratings ``sweeps,'' CBS' prime time programs, its late-night ``The
Pat Sajak Show'' and ``CBS This Morning'' all were third in network
ratings.
   Although some CBS programs like ``Murphy Brown'' and the
recently returned ``Beauty and the Beast'' have won critical
praise, CBS hasn't had a hit series since the debut of ``Murder,
She Wrote'' in 1984.
</TEXT>
