<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Quake     12-16 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Quake,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake in the Philippines Collapses Houses, Kills At Least One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake today rocked the
southern Philippines, crumbling parts of buildings and killing a
7-year-old boy.
   Coastal residents fled their homes in fear of tidal waves and
aftershocks, radio stations said.
   The quake measured 7.3 on the Richter scale and was felt
throughout eastern Mindanao, the second largest Philippine island,
and as far north as Legaspi City, 400 miles away, said Raymundo
Punongbayan, director of the Philippine Institute of Vulcanology
and Seismology.
   Punongbayan said the institute's observatory station in Bislig,
570 miles southeast of Manila, reported cracks on the walls and
slight damage to instruments. He said a concrete wall of a nearby
building collapsed, crushing the 7-year-old boy.
   Red Cross and government officials had no other reports of
damage or casualties in the remote area, which has poor
communication links with the capital, Manila.
   In Golden, Colo., the U.S. Geological Survey said the quake was
centered in the Pacific about 40 miles off northeast Mindanao and
160 miles from Davao. The city is 560 miles southeast of Manila.
   At least eight houses near the area also reported minor damages.
There were reports of widespread power outages in Mindanao,
Punongbayan added.
   The government's Philippine Information Agency said an abandoned
one-story building in Davao collapsed, injuring a passer-by.
   ``We are fortunate that the earthquake struck a sparsely
populated area,'' Punongbayan said. ``It could have caused serious
damage if it had hit a city.''
   Manila radio station DZXL said residents, fearful of tidal
waves, fled their homes for higher ground when the tremor was felt.
   Lino Abraham, a researcher for the seismological institute
office in Bislig, told DZXL that several aftershocks measuring
about 3 on the Richter scale were also felt. He said the quake
triggered landslides and the Pacific swelled after the quake, but
there were no reports of tidal waves.
   It was the biggest earthquake in that area since a quake
registering 6.8 hit Nov. 7, 1976, causing minor damage.
   In August 1976, a quake measuring 7.9 struck near the
southwestern coast of Mindanao caused a tidal wave that killed
about 8,000 people. A magnitude 7.1 earthquake in western Mindanao
the next day caused some injuries and damage.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an earthquake
and each increase of one number means the ground motion is 10 times
greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in a populated
area while one of magnitude 7 is capable of causing widespread
heavy damage.
   The quake that struck the San Francisco area in October was 7.1.
</TEXT>
