<DOCNO> AP891216-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 0927EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     12-16 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Patriarchs Restrict Christmas Celebrations; Collaborator Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian patriarchs of Jerusalem and the Holy
Land have decided to cancel festive Christmas visits and limit
other celebrations in sympathy with Palestinians who lost relatives
in the uprising.
   The Roman Catholic Patriarchate made the announcement as
violence continued in the occupied lands. One Arab was slain by
fellow Palestinians on the outskirts of Jerusalem, and five
Israeli-owned cars were set ablaze.
   Police said the 46-year-old Palestinian whose body was found in
Jabel Mukaber village was apparently suspected of collaborating
with Israel. His name was not released.
   It was the first killing of a suspected collaborator in the
Israeli-annexed part of the city, and it brought to 159 the number
of such kilings during the two-year uprising. In addition, 631
Palestinians have been killed by Israeli gunfire and 43 Israelis
have died.
   In Jewish west Jerusalem, arsonists believed to be Palestinians
set fire to five Israeli-owned vehicles overnight, police said. In
the last few months, more than 120 cars have been burned in the
area, and police believe Arab assailants have been responsible in
most cases.
   The Jerusalem office of the Roman Catholic patriarch, Michel
Sabbah, said Sabbah met with the Greek Orthodox patriarch of
Jerusalem, Diodoros I, and other religious officials to discuss the
``deteriorating situation'' in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Sabbah is the first Arab to head the Catholic Church in
Jerusalem.
   The patriarchs decided to issue a Christmas message voicing the
need for justice and peaceful settlement of the conflict; to
restrict Christmas celebrations to liturgical services and prayers
for justice and peace; and to cancel all Christmas visits and other
festivities ``in sympathy with those who mourn their beloved
ones,'' a statement said.
   The decision followed Thursday's announcement in Bethlehem and
neighboring Beit Sahour that Christmas celebrations would be
canceled for the third year in a row to support the uprising.
   In Gaza City and several towns in the West Bank, Palestinians
staged a five-minute traffic stoppage today following a call from
the uprising's underground leadership to commemorate ``martyrs'' of
the conflict, Arab and Israeli reports said.
   Arab journalists said Israeli troops tried to order the vehicles
to drive on and were met with a barrage of stones and shouts of
``Allahu Akbar,'' or God is great.
   Soldiers fired into the air and threw grenades, finally
resorting to live ammunition and plastic bullets, witnesses said.
In Gaza's hospitals, officials reported they treated five wounded
Arabs. The army said it had no information about the injuries.
   Soldiers also blocked entrances to the largest West Bank city,
Nablus, to prevent a group of Israelis from the leftist Peace Now
movement from meeting with Palestinians. The army said the Israelis
were kept out because Nablus was declared a closed military zone
and only residents could enter.
</TEXT>
