<FIRST>d i AM-BRF--Indonesia-Ship     12-16 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Indonesia-Ship,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Save All 85 Aboard Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers saved all 85 people aboard a
wooden ship which sank in the Java Sea, with only six suffering
slight injuries, the search mission coordinator center said
Saturday.
   The 33-ton Batam Jaya, which also carried cement and iron bars,
left the port of Sunda Kelapa in northern Jakarta Thursday night
for Batam Island and sank after developing a leak off the Seribu
Islands early Friday.
   Rescuers deployed three helicopters and two planes in the search
effort and were joined by coast guard and private ships. The sunken
ship was discovered off Jaga Utara Island, about 80 miles northwest
of Jakarta.
   Rescue teams saved all 85 people aboard, including 17 crew
members, air force Col. A. Siregar said. Six suffered minor
injuries while trying to save themselves, he said.
   Earlier reports counted only 75 people, including 15 crew
members aboard the ship.
</TEXT>
