<SECOND>PM-BRF--Helicopter Hovering, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0473,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Break World Helicopter Hovering Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT group's name to National Aeronautic
sted Aeronautics Association.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four pilots have set a world record by
staying aloft more than 50 hours in a Bell 47B helicopter at
Anaheim Stadium. The old mark was 47 hours and one second.
   Eggs were attached under each wheel of the helicopter as
required by the National Aeronautic Association to ensure the 1946
chopper never touched ground. The NAA certifies record flights.
   The helicopter landed at 4:44 p.m. Friday, setting the record
and raising $200,000 for charity.
   Each pilot took a four-hour shift, then was relieved for twelve
hours. The men stepped up ramps so the chopper could keep hovering.
The aircraft hovered an average of seven feet off the ground.
</TEXT>
