<DOCNO> AP891216-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-German-Unification Bjt   12-16 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German-Unification, Bjt,0939</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two States Proceeding with Giant Strides Toward Reunification</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Europe tries to come to grips with the
idea of German reunification, the two states are broadening ties so
swiftly that reunification already seems under way.
   Washington and Moscow insist they have a say in the process, but
neither Bonn nor East Berlin is paying much attention to the
superpowers in the daily rush of changes.
   Not a day has passed in recent weeks without a visit or another
series of agreements, although East German Communists loudly insist
the contacts will stop short of a formal union.
   The cooperation ranges from large industrial projects to plans
for single subway tickets for West Berlin and East Berlin, and
completion of autobahn links broken off by World War II.
   For many countries, though, the memories of war and Holocaust
are still too fresh to make the prospect of a united Germany a
pleasing one.
   The country would have 80 million people in the heart of Europe
and an economic might that would dwarf its neighbors. Fears about
an emerging ``Fourth Reich'' have been voiced.
   ``Our neighbors are worried and their fears are justified,''
says noted West German political scientist Joachim Perels.
   Josef Janning, an expert on East-West relations at the
University of Mainz, says fears of what reunification would bring
are exaggerated, but agrees West Germany must consult with other
countries on its policy toward East Germany.
   ``Until recently, politicians made perfunctory statements about
unity but no one really took it seriously until a few months ago,''
he told The Associated Press.
   ``But now that the Germans are discovering their own national
policy, there are justifications for fears. Bonn should not make
any unilateral moves without consultations,'' he said.
   ``But some sort of German unity cannot be prevented, not even
the Germans can prevent it.''
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl angered some governments by proposing a
10-point plan for eventual reunification without consulting Bonn's
allies.
   European leaders have passed resolutions that hardly hide their
fears of a mighty German state dominating Europe. U.S. officials
have said American and Soviet interests and rights must be
considered and Secretary of State James A. Baker III has urged a
go-slow approach to German reunification.
   The Soviets, who have nearly 400,000 soldiers in East Germany,
have issued stern warnings against Western intereference in East
German developments and have clearly stated they are against
reunification.
   The leaders of the 12 European Economic Community countries have
agreed that reunification must come through self-determination of
the people in the two Germanys and in consultation with other
European countries.
   The European Parliament has urged West Germany to state
``quickly and unambiguously'' that the reunification would stop
short of its former eastern territories that were lost in the war
and now belong to Poland and the Soviet Union.
   Meanwhile, in East Germany, weekly demonstrations have
increasingly become more nationalistic.
   ``Germany United Fatherland,'' thousands of people have shouted
at mass rallies the past four Mondays in Leipzig, the hotbed of the
East German opposition movement. Calls for quick reunification have
been made at other rallies in the country.
   At the last Leipzig rally, angry exchanges broke out between
supporters and opponents of reunification, and the opposition
movement has said it fears a split in its ranks over the issue.
   Free elections in East Germany have been set for May 6, 1990,
and at least two opposition groups have spoken in favor of
reunification.
   East Germany's Communist-dominated government officially remains
opposed to reunification, but at the same time it has gone on to
broaden ties with Bonn at all levels.
   When holes began opening in the Berlin Wall, East Berlin and
West Berlin police quickly established contact to deal with traffic
problems and other matters.
   ``What belongs together will grow together,'' former West German
Chancellor Willy Brandt said after the opening of the Berlin Wall,
in a much quoted remark.
   Even before Kohl goes to East Germany this week, cooperation
between the two states has proceeded at a rapid pace.
   Volkswagen, West Germany's biggest auto maker, has signed an
agreement to cooperate in developing a new generation of East
German Trabant cars. Dresdner Bank, the second-largest bank in West
Germany, is considering opening branches in East Germany.
   West German Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann visited East
Berlin last week and the two sides agreed to set up a joint
economic commission to expand cooperation.
   Bonn has promised $580 million for a project to clean up East
Germany's badly polluted environment.
   Lufthansa and Interflug, the two flag carriers, are adding new
flights between the two countries nearly every week.
   In a once-unthinkable move, Lufthansa joined with Interflug in
placing a full-page advertisement in Neues Deutschland, the
Communist Party newspaper.
   A fast rail link between Berlin and Hanover is under
consideration. A daily bus connection between Rostock in East
Germany and Kiel in West Germany started last week. From January 1,
West Germans will not need visas to visit East Germany.
   Perels, the political scientist, urges a slowdown in the current
breakneck speed.
   ``We have a special historical responsibility toward our
neighbors. We are not like any other country, we had the death
camps,'' Perels told The AP.
   ``For our democracy we have to thank the Allies. This is
something we often forget,'' Perels said, urging Germans to heed
concerns voiced by those in Washington, London and elsewhere.
</TEXT>
