<FIRST>r w AM-East-WestPhilanthropy     12-16 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West Philanthropy,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Foundations Helping in Soviet Union, Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American foundations are launching a series of
initiatives to encourage the political, social and economic changes
sweeping through the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   Efforts by foundations and private philanthropists range from
assisting pig farmers in Poland to fighting the spread of AIDS in
the Soviet Union and arranging exchanges between U.S. Vietnam
veterans and Soviet veterans of the Afghanistan war.
   The recent initiatives were capped by last week's announcement
by the Ford Foundation that it was committing an additional $6
million for grants to individuals and organizations in the region _
focusing on legal and political reforms, economics and the
environment.
   Franklin A. Thomas, president of the major New York-based
foundation, said the changes offer it ``many important
opportunities to contribute to the development of democratic values
and pluralism in the region and to the integration of the Soviet
Union and East European countries into the international system.''
   Also last week, the Carnegie Corporation of New York hosted a
two-day conference of U.S. foundation officials, business
executives, government officials and academics to help map further
philanthropic initiatives.
   At least two American foundations dealing with the Soviet Union
are pursuing programs with Moscow-based affiliates that have gained
official status under Soviet law as independent philanthropic
organizations.
   One of them, the San Francisco-based Foundation for Social
Innovations USA, was formed last June to work together with a
foundation started two years earlier in the Soviet Union with
sponsorship by the Moscow newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda, a
different publication from the often-quoted Pravda.
   The groups have launched programs including an exchange of
veterans of the Afghanistan and Vietnam wars, as well as a project
operated jointly with the Esalen Institute to help veterans and
disaster victims cope with post-traumatic stress problems.
   Henry S. Dakin, a San Francisco philanthropist who has been a
major contributor to the U.S.-Soviet effort, said the Foundation
for Social Innovations also has organized an Alaska-Siberia project
to help revive travel and people-to-people contacts over that
frontier.
   The New York-based Soros Foundation-Soviet Union was founded in
1987 by George Soros, a Hungarian emigre who became wealthy as a
money manager on Wall Street. It has supported the launching of a
Soviet counterpart, the Cultural Initiative, with headquarters at a
restored 17th-century mansion in central Moscow.
   Programs being undertaken by the Soros-funded organizations
include bringing young Soviet attorneys to this country for
internships at American law firms; assisting a
wheelchair-manufacturing project in Leningrad; and providing
American-made disposable hypodermic needles to Soviet hospitals.
   ``This was a response to a growing sense of urgency in the
Soviet Union about AIDS and ways of controlling it,'' said Anthony
Richter, a Soros Foundation program officer.
   Concern about acquired immune deficiency syndrome has been
heightened in the Soviet Union by recent incidents in which
children in Soviet hospitals were infected through the re-use of
unsterilized needles.
   In addition, Richter said the Soros Foundation has launched a
``very promising'' program to train Soviet medical professionals in
the use of American-developed methods for treating alcoholics.
   Soros also founded in 1984 a foundation dealing with his native
Hungary, where that organization has begun projects to help
independent organizations and small businesses get started and has
broadened its program supporting English-language instruction.
   Other American foundations currently funding programs in Eastern
Europe include the Rockefeller Brothers Fund, the German Marshall
Fund of the United States and the John D. and Catherine T.
MacArthur Foundation.
   In Poland, the Rockefeller Brothers Fund, which has spent about
$4 million on Eastern Europe since 1983, assisted in the formation
of a new Warsaw-based Foundation for the Development of Polish
Agriculture.
   John Edie, general counsel of the Council on Foundations, a
Washington-based organization of 1,200 grant-making institutions,
said the Polish group has ``really been a stimulation to the hog
farmers. They chose that because Polish ham is a very popular
export.''
   Edie said American foundations were most interested in
encouraging wider development of an independent sector in the
Soviet Union and Eastern Europe, because ``the more independent
thinking and initiative there is in those countries, the easier it
is going to be for them to continue the direction they're going
toward.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
