<FIRST>u a PM-StormsRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0465 12-16 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Storms Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arctic Onslaught Snarls Traffic, Closes Schools, Offices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE death toll, snowfall totals, record
low temperatures. Picks up 6th graf, `The cold....' Adds details of two
additional deaths in penultimate graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An arctic onslaught of snow and cold continued to refrigerate
much of the East and Midwest today, after heavy weather snarled
traffic and forced closure of schools, government offices and even
racetracks.
   Four traffic deaths and two related to snow and cold were blamed
on the weather Friday.
   ``An Arctic air mass out of Alaska and northern Canada has been
sitting over the middle United States and shows no inclination to
move,'' Weather Service forecaster Larry Hildebrand said in
Chicago. ``We're running about 30 degrees below normal for this
time of year.''
   Up to 8 inches of snow piled up by this morning from New England
south into Virginia and from Michigan and Wisconsin into Kentucky,
according to the National Weather Service. Boston had 3 inches, and
central Massachusetts got as much as 8 inches, as did east-central
Wisconsin.
   Wind and cold overnight made it feel as cold as 10 degrees below
zero in northern Arkansas and northwest Texas, and the wind-chill
was expected to dive to 20 below in parts of Tennessee.
   Overnight lows included 14 degrees below zero at Kansas City
International Airport and 3 below at Bluefield, W.Va. St. Louis'
reading of 8 below broke the record for the date. In Kansas, lows
of 16 below at Salina and 15 below at Topeka set records.
   Record temperatures measured in Texas today included 9 degrees
in Abilene, 11 at Waco, 12 at Midland and the Dallas-Fort Worth
airport, 17 at Austin and San Antonio, 19 at Houston, 24 at Corpus
Christi and 33 at Brownsville, the state's southernmost town on the
Mexican border.
   The cold blast on Friday dumped snow on much of the Midwest and
East, and from the Rocky Mountain states to northern New Mexico.
   Snow and ice made driving hazardous in many areas, forcing
authorities to close schools and offices.
   Government offices and courts closed in parts of Ohio and
Pennsylvania, horse or harness races were canceled in Ohio and
Pennsylvania. The Ku Klux Klan called off a rally planned for
Oxford, Ohio, saying it was because of cold.
   Students got the day off from school in parts of Wyoming,
Kansas, Missouri, Nebraska, Illinois, Wisconsin, Indiana, Ohio,
Kentucky and West Virginia.
   Authorities at the Wheeling-Ohio County Airport in West
Virginia's Northern Panhandle planned to dedicate $170,000 worth of
snow removal equipment Friday, but the ceremony was postponed
because the equipment was put to work.
   ``Priorities are such that we need to get our runways clean,''
said airport manager Thomas Tominack.
   Traffic snarled in many areas as big rigs jackknifed on icy
highways and cars skidded into fender-benders.
   Indiana authorities blamed two traffic deaths Friday on the
weather. In Glenwillow, Ohio, police blamed icy roads for a crash
that killed a woman. Wyoming officials said a man was killed Friday
afternoon when his automobile slid off of Interstate 80 and
overturned.
   The cold wave chased thousands of the nation's homeless into
crowded shelters. Two deaths in St. Louis were blamed on the snow
and cold.
   In Chicago, where temperatures didn't climb out of the single
digits Friday, all but 260 of the city's 3,400 beds in shelters and
churches were filled Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891216-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Imbalances     12-16 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Imbalances,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EST, TIME set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>UN Experts Ask Basic Change in US Savings, European Jobs, Asian Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of experts from the United States,
Britain and South Korea joined Saturday in urging a drive to reduce
the numbers of Europe's 18 million unemployed.
   ``Europe's long-term unemployed represent its greatest untapped
resorde,'' they said.
   The group consists of economists Olivier Blanchard, Rudiger
Dornbusch and Paul Krugman of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology; Mervyn King and Richard Layard of the London School of
Economics; Lawrence H. Summers of Harvard University; and Yung Chul
Park of Korea University in Seoul.
   Their report, ``World Imbalances,'' was sponsored by World
Institute for Development Economics Research, set up in Helsinki,
Finland, as part of the United Nations University.
   They suggested use of a Swedish model to fight unemployment:
intensive placement, conseling and retraining services for people
who lose their jobs; unemployment benefits that run out in 14
months; six months of public employment if no job has been found;
and a 50 percent wage subsidy lasting six months for employers who
hire people who have been out of work for six months.
   ``Unemployment in Sweden has never been over 3.5 percent and now
stands under 1.5 percent,'' the authors said.
   For the United States they recommended an emphasis on increased
savings. Low U.S. savings and the accompanying high federal budget
deficit create a worldwide shortage of capital, threaten the world
trading system and are a likely source of instability in the world
economy, they said.
   In addition to reducing the federal budget deficit, they
suggested:
   _ removing social security and its surpluses from the federal
budget, so that the apparent budget deficit is greater and public
pressure increases to lower it;
   _ restoring the Individual Retirement Account; and
   _ instituting tax incentives for savings, such as a deduction
for employees who as part of their wages will accept stock that
cannot be sold for five years, or a deduction for investment in
special Treasury notes that could not he'sold.
   They have a radical proposal for Third World debt, now close to
$1.3 trillion. They would allow interest payments to be made in the
currency of the debtor countries, rather than in hard currencies
like dollars or yen which are now required.
   They said the effect would be to:
   _ stop transfers of funds from debtor countries to creditors,
now running over $50 billion a year;
   _ reduce the uncertainty of exchange rates, thus encouraging the
return of billions of dollars sent abroad for safekeeping by people
in debtor countries; and
   _ free the foreign currency held by debtor countries for
purchases of goods in the creditor countries.
   In the Pacific they warned that a cut in the U.S. budget could
bring recession to East Asia. They recommended coordinating the
policies of the United States and East Asian countries on how
production should be distributed among them.
   To prevent the world trading system from breaking into regional
blocs centered on the United States, Japan and the European
Economic Community, they urged:
   _ quick reduction of the U.S. trade deficit, and reduction of
surpluses in Japan, West Germany and the industrializing countries
of East Asia;
   _ easing of what they called the intransigence of the Europeans
on trade in farm products; and
   _ further increases in imports into Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
