<FIRST>r a AM-BlackSanta     12-16 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Santa,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mall Apologizes to Black Santa for Alleged Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER HILLS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shopping center is asking a black
Santa Claus to return, issuing a public apology to the man who quit
last week because he said the mall objected to his skin color.
   Derrick L. Trice walked off the job Tuesday as one of three
Santas at Capital Plaza Mall in Prince George's County, saying he
wouldn't return unless he received such an apology.
   The mall issued a public statement Friday, saying it ``in no way
intended to convey the message that Mr. Trice's services were not-
anted or that he was not welcome to return to his position as
Santa Claus. If Mr. Trice received this impression, the mall
regrets that and extends its apology to Mr. Trice.''
   Trice, 21, met with the county branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People on Friday.
Richard Steve Brown, president of the NAACP branch, told The
(Baltimore) Sun he planned to pursue the incident with the mall's
owners this week.
   Trice could not be reached for comment; his telephone number was
not in local directories.
   Mall manager Thomas A. Breece issued the apology but said he has
not spoken with Trice and did not know if he would return.
   Trice said he confronted the mall's managers after a mall
security guard came by his post to ask ``how long the black Santa
would be around.'' He said he was shown the door after an argument
with Breece.
   Officials at the mall said the incident came about after
customers _ both black and white _ complained about the black
Santa. Trice was asked to leave the mall office because he was very
upset, according to the statement.
   ``The Capital Plaza Mall continues to believe that it is
appropriate to have Santas of all races,'' the mall's statement
said. ``The mall sincerely hopes that Mr. Trice will return and
continue to serve its customers.''
</TEXT>
