<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     12-16 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President: Trust Bush on China Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle is predicting that
within six months to a year, events in China will vindicate
President Bush for his much-criticized overtures to Beijing.
   ``In due time, critics will see this as the right decision at
the right time,'' Quayle said Friday when asked about the
widespread criticism of Bush for sending two top-level envoys to
Beijing last weekend.
   In so doing, the president opened the door to renewal of ties
with China little more than six months after the Chinese government
used tanks to quell pro-democracy demonstrations, killing hundreds,
possibly thousands of people.
   The vice president would not give details but hinted that U.S.
officials in the wake of the weekend visit know of some forthcoming
developments that will show an improved Chinese posture on human
rights and political freedoms.
   ``China took a step backwards with the Tiananmen Square
tragedy,'' Quayle said in the interview. ``China hopefully will
have the political reforms reinstituted and China will move
forward. My prediction is that the president's bold initiative
toward China will be fully appreciated within the long run by the
American people.''
   Bush quietly dispatched National Security Adviser Brent
Scowcroft and Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger to
Beijing a week ago Friday, in a departure from the ban on
high-level contacts with China that he imposed after the Tiananmen
Square massacre.
   The visit was intended to begin discussions on normalizing
relations, but U.S. officials have said that will not happen and
the sanctions against China will not be lifted until China shows
improvement in political reform and human rights.
   Quayle insisted that Bush, a former envoy to China, ``knows what
he is doing'' and had made a ``strategic and tactical decision.''
   As to what indications China has given that it might be open to
U.S. pressures for change, he said, ``Watch what happens.''
   ``It takes time,'' he said. ``In the long run, looking at the
big picture, looking forward, having an idea of what the world is
going to look like six months and a year from now, the president
will be fully vindicated in his decision. I am hopeful that you
will see progress in China.''
   As to why the administration is willing to deal with a country
that has gone in the opposite direction while reforms sweep other
communist nations, Quayle said China is ``probably ahead'' of the
Soviet Union in economic reforms. But he acknowledged, ``As far as
the political context, the advancement of human rights, of allowing
peaceful dissent, sensitivity toward civil rites, China has got to
move forward.''
   Quayle was asked why the attitude is different toward China from
what it is toward Cuba and Nicaragua, two small countries that come
under frequent and harsh attack by Bush for being out of step with
democratic movement in this hemisphere.
   Quayle said China is important as the world's most populous
country, with nuclear capability and a common border with the
Soviet Union.
   ``The president is interested in advancing human rights in China
and he knows full well that to advance human rights and make
progress you have to be engaged rather than sitting on the side
lines.''
   Quayle also said that in looking at the coming year, the
administration's toughest foreign policy challenge will be the
debate over Central America, particularly Nicaragua.
   The administration remains skeptical, he said, that the ruling
Sandinistas will hold fair elections in February as promised. The
elections will be an important factor in Bush's decision whether to
resume aid to the Contra rebels who have been trying to topple the
Sandinistas for the past eight years.
   Quayle noted Bush supports the diplomatic approach endorsed by
Congress and the presidents of the five Central American nations,
but also that ``you don't rule out any options including Contra
aid.''
   ``The elections will be very important, how they're conducted,
if they're held, what (Nicaraguan President Daniel) Ortega does
during the election process, on election day and thereafter,'' he
said.
   Domestically, Quayle said, the administration's toughest
challenge next year will be keeping the economy moving forward.
</TEXT>
