<HEAD>Disney Family Treasures Destroyed in House Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasured Walt Disney family memorabilia,
including early original drawings by the famous cartoonist, burned
in a house fire, family members said.
   ``The home was a showcase,'' said Melinda Carfagno,
granddaughter of a retired Disney executive whose suburban home
burned Friday. William Cottrell, 83, was treated at the scene and
was staying with a neighbor, Ms. Carfagno said.
   The blaze in the Toluca Lake area, about 10 miles northwest of
downtown, was blamed on a faulty furnace, Fire Department spokesman
Pat Marek said.
   Damage to the house and furnishings was estimated at about
$250,000, fire officials said. The Disney artifacts defy cost
estimates because they were irreplaceable, Ms. Carfagno said.
   ``He lived here for 26 years. There was a priceless collection
of antiques and original drawings and photos from the company,''
Ms. Carfagno said. ``It was an incredible archive.''
   Cottrell was married to Hazel Sewell, an older sister of
Disney's wife, Lillian. He retired in 1982 as head of the
family-owned Retlaw Corp., whose name is Walter spelled backward.
