<FIRST>r w AM-NursingStudents     12-16 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Students,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Nursing School Enrollment Increase in Five Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enrollment of new students in college and
university nursing programs rose for the first time in five years,
but this year's increase is too little to overcome an acute nursing
shortage, according to a survey released Sunday.
   The American Association of Colleges of Nursing said enrollment
of first-time nursing students in universities and four-year
colleges rose by 5.8 percent in the current 1989-1990 academic
year. About 60,522 new nursing students are pursuing the
baccalaureate degree, both full- and part-time, this year, compared
with 57,154 in the 1988-1989 academic year, an advance copy of the
survey showed.
   Combined baccalaureate enrollment, including first-time students
and registered nurses returning for bachelor degrees, is 89,546 in
the current academic year, compared with 87,700 a year ago, an
increase of 2.1 percent.
   ``Student enrollment may be in the early stages of an upturn,''
said Association Director Geraldine Bednash, but she added, ``the
road to reversing the nation's acute nursing shortage remains a
long one.''
   Baccalaureate enrollment fell an ``alarming 31.9 percent'' from
1984 to 1988,'' but Ms. Bednash said enrollment increases this year
reduced that five-year slide to 17.7 percent.
   ``Overall shortages in student enrollment and in the nursing
work force will likely continue for several years,'' Ms. Bednash
said.
   In 1988, total graduations of first-time nurses with
baccalaureate degrees were 16.2 percent lower than the year before.
In 1989, graduations of first-time students _ about 16,003 _ were
still 11.3 percent below 1988 figures.
   Officials said the survey is based on data received in fall 1989
from 538 of the nation's 623 nursing schools with four-year
bachelor's degree and graduate degree programs. The association,
with more than 400 member institutions nationwide, said the report
represents 124,927 full-time and part-time students in both member
and non-member institutions in 50 states, the District of Columbia,
and U.S. territories.
   ``This is the second consecutive year in which enrollment
figures have shown some improvement,'' said Ms. Bednash. She
explained that nursing schools in the 1988-89 academic year had 7.9
percent fewer baccalaureate students enrolled than the year before,
but the decline was greatly less than the 14.5 percent drop seen
from 1986-87.
   Most registered nurses pursue continued education part-time, but
the survey indicated a dramatic 44.7 percent increase in RNs _
those with hospital diplomas or two-year associate degrees _ who
returned to school full-time during the last five years to earn the
baccalaureate degree. In 1985, there were 4,151 RNs who returned,
compared with 6,010 in 1989.
   ``The data reflect the growing numbers of nurses who are
furthering their education full-time to keep pace with the
increasing complexities and treatment and technological advances in
today's health care system,'' said the survey.
   Ms. Bednash said, ``The signs of change are promising, including
expanded interest in nursing as a rewarding and secure career as
seen in increased student applications to schools of nursing.''
   For the current academic year, qualified applicants totaled
16,962, compared with 14,813 in 1988-89, an increase of 14.5
percent. The numbers of students accepted by schools of nursing
this year _ at 14,717 _ increased by 14.4 percent over last year's
total of 12,861.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
