<DOCNO> AP891216-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria     12-16 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgarians Demand Funeral Service for Victims of Stalin Purges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several thousand protesters Saturday
demanded an official funeral service for the victims of Stalinist
purges, including a Communist Party chief who was hanged after a
show trial 40 years ago.
   The demand from members of the pro-democracy movement came
during a rally in Sofia commemorating the former party leader,
Traicho Kostov, who was convicted of spying and stirring up
hostility against the Soviet Union.
   An unidentified speaker at the rally accused Vasil Kolarov, who
was premier at the time, of conspiring to arrange Kostov's
execution on Nov. 16, 1949, and of sending hundreds of people to
Stalinist camps in the Soviet Union.
   Others said Kostov was killed because he resisted Soviet orders
on trade.
   The crowd chanted ``We want the names of the killers!''
expressing outrage over a Stalinist terror campaign in Bulgaria in
the 1940s and early 1950s.
   Around the time of the Kostov trial, 1,080 people, including
party and military officials, were prosecuted, the official news
agency BTA said Friday. No official publication has ever said how
many poeple died in the purges.
   The rally came amid swift political developments in Bulgaria,
where hard-line Communist Party leaders were ousted in the face of
large pro-democracy demonstrations. In one concession, officials
condemned the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion of neighboring
Czechoslovakia, saying ``history has proved it to be wrong and
incompatible with the new course'' of the Bulgarian Communist Party.
   A resolution adopted at the rally Saturday said a bust of Kostov
should replace a memorial to Kolarov located behind the mausoleum
of national hero Georgi Dimitrov in the center of Sofia. It also
called for erecting a ``monument to all victims of the Stalinist
system in Bulgaria.''
   The resolution demanded that a commission be formed to
investigate and publish all crimes committed during the Stalinist
years in Bulgaria.
   Kostov was Bulgaria's most prominent victim of show trials
organized in Eastern Europe at the time at the request of Soviet
dictator Josef Stalin.
   The aim of these purges was to liquidate those leaders who
advocated a ``national road to socialism'' in their respective
countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
