<FIRST>r w AM-BabyCosts     12-16 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Costs,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Costs Racing Ahead of Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies are becoming luxuries, with the cost of
getting them through just the first year nearly double what it was
a generation ago, according to a business magazine.
   In their first year of life babies cost $5,774 in goods and
services, reports American Demographics, a magazine that analyzes
consumer trends.
   A Department of Agriculture study calculates the cost of a
baby's first year at between $5,096 and $5,602, but researcher Mark
Lino says that analysis is being updated and the figures are
expected to increase.
   A Life magazine report in 1958 calculated the cost of baby's
first year at just $800 worth of goods and services.
   Allowing for inflation, that would be $2,892 today.
   And once parents opt for this luxury there's no turning back,
with the cost of raising a child through age 18 estimated at
$100,000, reports Blayne Cutler, a senior editor of American
Demographics.
   Nonetheless, Americans produced 3.9 million offspring last year,
according to the National Center for Health Statistics. That was a
2 percent increase from the year before, although short of the 4.2
million births recorded in 1958.
   In his comparison with the costs of 1958, Cutler observes that
parents today face expenses that wouldn't have occurred 30 years
ago.
   ``Few families needed day care 30 years ago. Today, more than
half of first-time mothers are back at work before their child
celebrates a first birthday,'' reported Cutler. Day care costs
today's parents an average of $53 a week.
   ``Car seats, disposable diapers, formula and sophisticated
photographic equipment also add to the expense facing first-time
parents,'' Cutler wrote.
   Car seats are required by law, infant formula is urged by
physicians and disposable diapers are demanded by harried parents,
Cutler said.
   During the first year the average baby requires 3,000 disposable
diapers, according to Cutler. These cost $570.
   Food and feeding equipment will cost parents $855, he estimated,
with a cost of $995 for furniture, $352 for clothing, $223 for
bedding and bath supplies, $396 for medicine and personal-care
products and $199 for toys.
   Cutler's estimates for baby's first year are close to, but a bit
higher than, those calculated by the government's Family Economics
Research Group.
   That agency figures getting an urban baby through its first year
would be least costly in the Northeast at $5,096. A baby would cost
$5,138 in the Midwest, $5,523 in the West and $5,602 in the South.
   Those figures take a set of 1960 estimates and update them for
inflation, explained Lino, who is currently updating the figures.
   ``We will be adding new items such as child care, that is
expected to be a big item,'' he said. In addition, extra costs will
be added in for such things as disposable diapers, car seats,
higher transportation costs and other items, he said.
   Over 18 years the West is the most expensive place to raise a
child, the Department of Agriculture figures.
   While Cutler used a national average of $100,000 for 18 years,
Lino calculated the cost of 18 years of parenting at $116,995 for
residents of the West, $114,483 in the South, $110,891 in the
Northeast and $105,055 in the Midwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
