<FIRST>r w AM-StudentMatch     12-16 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student Match,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Get Help With Colleges, Career Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A university wants to recruit minority high
school graduates with a special interest in volleyball, even though
their math and science grades may be just average.
   A soon-to-graduate high school senior wants to stay near home
and pursue a career in nursing but doesn't know where to find
information on the best vocational education courses.
   Richard Frazier, founder and chairman of Collegiate Research
Services Inc., likes to think he can help both with his new
computer service, ACCES, the American Career and College Entry
Service.
   Sophomores and juniors at participating high schools complete,
free of charge, a 45-minute, 23-page survey that details their
future education and career interests and preferences. Frazier said
in a recent interview that the survey goes beyond standardized test
scores, grade point average and geographical location.
   Colleges, universities and trade schools use the student
profiles to try to determine who will likely succeed at their
institutions.
   Nearly 14,000 high schools had registered to participate by the
end of November and the goal is to have 17,000 high schools
throughout the United States and American overseas schools around
the world by January, said Frazier, who wants to have about 4
million students profiled in the one-line computer network.
   By next fall, information will be available to post-secondary
institutions that pay fees ranging from $2,000 to $6,000 a year.
The goal is to have 4,000 subscribers by late next year, said
Frazier.
   ``ACCES is for the entire student population,'' he said. ``There
are very few programs offered that have benefits for every single
student across the entire class. That's what makes it unique.''
   Frazier recalls his own unpleasant experience contemplating life
after high school.
   His admission application was rejected by Brown University. ``I
was a very good student but scored poorly'' on college entrance
exams, he said.
   ``I think `Gee, if someone had taken the time to say here is a
kid with good grades, still working and attending a competitive
high school,' perhaps I would have stood more of a chance,'' said
Frazier, who eventually enrolled in Norwich University, a military
college in Vermont, before transferring to Catholic University
   With ACCES, he said, ``We're hoping to accomplish two things:
get these students involved early on in their high school years _
get them thinking and planning their journey beyond high school.''
   Recruiters can find those students who usually are missed or
overlooked because they have no plans to take college entrance
tests or have bleak chances of graduating, they said.
   ``We're giving these institutions a way to identify students
they never had before and we're giving them information in a
manageable format,'' said Grogan.
   ACCES was designed over a period of four years, evolving from a
service focusing on students with special needs. Assisting in the
project was a national advisory council of educators, business
leaders and policymakers from such organizations as the National
Council of Educational Opportunity Associations, the Committee for
Economic Development, and the National Association of Secondary
School Principals.
   David Dunaway of the secondary school principals group said that
although the program is ``very intriguing,'' the organization has
declined to endorse the service until further review.
   ACCES ``has the potential to be an outstanding product,'' added
Dunaway, principal of Benjamin Russell High School in Alexander
City, Ala. He said his school has not subscribed because of
concerns over the security of the information given by the students
and the time needed for the students to complete the survey.
   As for security, Frazier said only postsecondary institutions
accredited by bodies recognized by the Department of Education or
the Council on Postsecondary Accreditation are eligible to
subscribe to the network. State employment and training agencies
also can join so students can learn about job training
opportunities or internships, he said.
</TEXT>
