<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Violence     12-16 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Violence,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Shooting, Killing Continues Despite 24-Hour Curfew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYDERABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed three people and
wounded about 20, police said Saturday, despite a shoot-on-sight
curfew aimed at quelling a week of ethnic violence in this southern
Pakistani city.
   Hospital sources said another person died of wounds inflicted
the day before, bringing the death toll to 15 since Monday.
   The fighting is between natives of Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto's home province of Sindh, and immigrants from India called
mohajirs. Authorities routinely refuse to state the ethnic origins
of victims in order to avoid reprisal killings.
   Police, speaking on the usual condition of anonymity, said
unidentified gunmen defied Saturday's curfew, killed two gas
station attendants and fled. A third man apparently was the victim
of a rooftop sniper.
   Police and army troops patrolled the narrow, squalid streets in
machine gun-mounted jeeps but there was sporadic shooting around
the city all day, eyewitnesses said.
   Authorities gave the shoot-on-sight order Friday, the Moslem
sabbath, after three people were killed and nine others were
wounded during a brief curfew break for prayers.
   Hundreds have been killed and thousands have been wounded in the
past three years in clashes between the two groups in Hyderabad and
Karachi, Pakistan's largest city 90 miles to the southwest.
   The mainly rural Sindhis claim the mohajirs have squeezed them
out of jobs, especially in urban areas. The mohajirs claim they are
victims of discrimination, and have called for the same official
ethnic status in Pakistan as native Sindhis, Punjabis, Baluchis and
Pathans.
</TEXT>
