<FIRST>r a AM-Mofford-Murderers     12-16 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mofford-Murderers,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov. Mofford Criticized for Commuting Sentences, Then Flip-Flopping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford's decision to commute the
prison terms of two convicted murderers and her sudden about-face
has voters, talk-show hosts and politicians questioning her
competence and political savvy.
   The 67-year-old Democrat was elevated to governor last year from
her largely ceremonial elected post as secretary of state upon the
impeachment conviction of Republican Evan Mecham. The questioning
of whether she is a lightweight or a leader comes as Mrs. Mofford
begins gearing up for an election campaign next year.
   The immediate furor centers on commutations Mrs. Mofford signed
several months ago that became public only recently.
   Carl Kummerlowe, 62, whose commutation was signed in May, had
been sentenced to life in prison for bludgeoning a service-station
manager to death in 1969, dismembering his body and packing it into
ice chests for disposal.
   James Hamm, whose commutation was signed in July, had been
sentenced to life in 1974 for killing two drug dealers near Tucson
to steal their profits.
   The Board of Pardons and Paroles had recommended the
commutations, saying both men had been model prisoners who had
rehabilitated themselves and deserved commutations so they could
become eligible for parole earlier.
   Mrs. Mofford said she knew both were murderers but says she
wasn't given the board's full report about them. Board officials
say detailed files on the men were supplied to her office and that
Mofford aides apparently summarized them for her.
   One lawmaker, Peter Goudinoff, says he thinks the storm will
blow over by election time next November.
   ``The real issues are down the road: budget, taxes and to some
degree (auto) insurance,'' says Goudinoff, a Democrat who teaches
political science at the University of Arizona when the Legislature
isn't meeting.
   But other lawmakers say Mrs. Mofford has wiped out any progress
she had made before the controversy.
   ``Everybody feels sorry for her,'' said Republican Leo Corbet,
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``She's a nice lady,
but she's about 12 leagues over her competency level.''
   Mrs. Mofford declined to be interviewed for this story. Her
in-house political expert, special assistant Rip Wilson, said,
``There's no question the governor can be staffed better.''
   When she first became chief executive, lawmakers and voters
found Mrs. Mofford's low-key style a welcome relief from the
constant controversy that swirled about Mecham, whose sharp tongue
alienated many minorities and other groups.
   But lawmakers criticized her after this year's first legislative
session as someone more interested in cutting ribbons than running
government.
   In October, when state agencies sought more than $1 billion in
spending hikes for next year despite a looming state financial
crisis, Republicans said the inflated budget requests were proof
that Mrs. Mofford couldn't manage her agencies.
   In November, Mrs. Mofford called lawmakers into special session
on auto insurance but abandoned it when the going got unexpectedly
rough.
   Just last week, Mrs. Mofford stunned state labor leaders who
form a key constituency when she accepted an award from an
anti-union group, the latest in a series of slaps at organized
labor.
   The commutations controversy might have blown over quickly if
Mrs. Mofford had stuck to her guns, lawmakers say. After all,
former Gov. Bruce Babbitt commuted the sentences of 26 convicts and
even the arch-conservative Mecham reduced a murderer's sentence.
   But Mrs. Mofford did an about-face when criticism of the
commutations arose, announcing Tuesday that she would take the
whole thing back if Attorney General Bob Corbin said she had the
authority to do so.
   Corbin did her one better, announcing Friday that he had found a
technical loophole to void the commutations retroactively before
they even got to Mrs. Mofford's desk. He found the victims'
families had not been properly notified of the pending commutations.
   The governor also made contradictory statements that left voters
puzzled.
   At one point, for example, she said that no murderer should be
allowed back on the streets. Minutes later, she said that she had
known that Kummerlowe and Hamm were murderers before she commuted
their sentences.
   Calls to radio talk shows were running heavily against Mrs.
Mofford. Some radio talk show hosts, like Bob Mohan of KFYI in
Phoenix, have blasted her for commuting the sentences. Others, like
KFYI's John Dayl, have accused her of ``hiding on the ninth floor,
curling up into a fetal position'' at the slightest criticism.
   There has even been criticism from the Democratic camp.
   Mrs. Mofford's floor leader in the House, minority leader Art
Hamilton, said, ``I think it would be less than honest not to admit
some concern.''
</TEXT>
