<DOCNO> AP891216-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Navy-ArmsControl     12-16 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy-Arms Control,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy's Top Officer Says `Nyet' To Naval Arms Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's top admiral says the Soviet Union
may be able to achieve much of what it wants in naval arms control
``by just sitting back and waiting'' for budget pressures to pare
away the U.S. fleet.
   ``It is not in the interest of this country to have a weak Navy,
or even a weaker Navy,'' Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost, the Chief of
Naval Operations, said in an interview last week in his Pentagon
office.
   The admiral, reviewing the results of the recent Malta summit,
firmly rejected any move towards entering naval arms control
discussions with the Soviets, a stance taken by President Bush in
his talks with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   In the interview, Trost also took a tough line on impending
budget cuts, contending it would be difficult to expect the service
to take on additional duties _ such as the war against drugs _ with
fewer ships and personnel.
   ``If we are to have the capability to respond ... as we are
called on repeatedly, we need the force we have now as the absolute
minimum,'' he said.
   If not, the admiral warned, ``you're meeting the same
commitments with fewer forces. ... Your ability to respond goes
down, the burden on your personnel goes up.''
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has been ordered to keep Pentagon
spending to $292 billion for the next fiscal year, a level 2
percent below the anticipated inflation rate.
   And in order to keep expenses in line with anticipated tight
budgets in the coming years of 1992 to 1994, the secretary has also
ordered the armed services to come up with plans to cut some $180
billion in projected spending over the coming years.
   The admiral declined to comment specifically on reports that the
service plans to meet Cheney's directive by cutting ship strength
from 562 ships to 500 _ including two to three aircraft carriers _
and Navy and Marine Corps manpower by 40,000.
   But he noted that the Soviets are keenly aware that economic
belt-tightening is in Washington's future.
   ``They do understand the political process,'' he said. ``They
can look to achieve much of what they want to achieve just by
sitting back and waiting.''
   Trost said the Soviets continue to press for naval arms control
``because their goal is to constrain the capability of the U.S.
Navy, which they have repeatedly stated is one of their greatest
concerns.''
   At Malta, the Soviets reportedly spelled out new, more stringent
conditions for an accord on submarine-launched cruise missiles,
indicating they want a deal on those weapons concluded in tandem
with a strategic weapons treaty that is supposed to be ready for a
summit in June.
   Trost rejected Soviet assertions that anti-cheating measures
could be worked out to check for the presence of nuclear-tipped
cruise missiles on ships or submarines. The admiral said there are
too many ways to cheat, or ``break out'' of the an agreement by
hiding the small, lethal weapons.
   ``The ability to verify such things as sea-launched cruise
missiles is nil,'' he said. ``(There's) no chance of coming up with
a good, comprehensive system that covers everything, at all times,
and guarantees against break-out.''
   The United States has also rejected the idea of allowing Soviets
on board their ships and submarines as ``too intrusive'' a way to
check for the presence of the weapons.
   ``Verification is a major problem,'' he said. ``It can't easily
be wished away.''
   The admiral, who delivered the same message directly to Soviet
naval officers during a six-day visit to the their country in
October, said President Gorbachev's push for curbs is a recognition
of the strength of the U.S. force, as well as economic pressure.
   ``What you're seeing is a reflection of an honest concern of the
capability _ the deterrent affect _ of a strong U.S. Navy ... and
the realization that competition with us is expensive,'' the
admiral said.
   To those who would say that the Soviet threat is lessening,
Trost argues: ``I remind them that the political statement of
threat has gone away, but the military capability remains. ...
(Even) if we see a total reduction of Soviet naval capability, ...
our requirement for a Navy remains, because we have a lot of people
around the world who aren't always friendly'' to U.S. interests.
   The admiral expressed some skepticism when asked about reports
that President Bush and other top members of the U.S. adminstration
have received intelligence reports for months saying the Soviets
had ordered defense cutbacks, but the officials continue to warn of
a growing Soviet threat.
   ``If there is such a nice, concrete black-and-white intelligence
result, I'd like to see it,'' Trost shot back.
</TEXT>
