<FIRST>r a AM-Tractors-Accidents     12-16 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tractors-Accidents,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Studying Accidents Roll Tractors Over Hill _ On TV Screen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Coddington flips tractors over,
rolls them down hills and wrecks them _ but the accidents he causes
are all on a computer screen. It's all part of a research project
to make the most deadly workplace, the farm, a little safer.
   Coddington and Bob Aherin, agricultural engineers at the
University of Illinois, developed the computer simulation so they
could observe factors that lead to accidents on the farm.
   Agriculture leads the National Safety Council's list of the most
deadly occupations. There were about 1,500 farm deaths and 140,000
disabling injuries nationwide in 1988, according to the
Chicago-based organization, which had no individual state figures.
   Tractor roll-overs are the leading accidental cause of
farm-related deaths in Illinois, accounting for about 30 percent of
them, according to the Country Companies Insurance Group of
Bloomington.
   ``The goal is to find out what contributes to an accident and
what protective devices will help the farmer,'' said Coddington.
``I would think manufacturers would find this useful in designing
new equipment.''
   The computer allows the researchers to specify things like the
weight, wheelbase and center of gravity of the tractor, plus the
slope of the hill. They take into consideration factors like wet,
slippery fields.
   ``I'd like to know if it is going to roll, how long it will take
and the total energy'' unleashed during the rollover, he said.
   Coddington punches in some data on his keyboard during a recent
test, and a tractor appears on the screen. Its right wheels slide
off the edge of a hill, its left wheels lift off the ground, then
bounce back down.
   ``It tried but it didn't turn over,'' he said. ``It tipped, then
rocked back.''
   The information is changed, and again the tractor tips.
   ``Now, as it goes past the point of no return, it will roll
over,'' said Coddington.
   What can make the difference between a tractor that rolls over
and one that stays on its wheels? A lower center of gravity and
wider wheel spacing can be designed by engineers, but they stress
that the care exhibited by the person behind the wheel is always a
factor, too.
   ``Manufacturers try to make their equipment safe and post
warnings about hazards,'' said Coddington. ``But people are crazy.
They'll use equipment in no way, shape or form the way it was
intended.''
   The computer simulation not only may help manufacturers design
safer equipment, but could increase farmers' awareness of dangerous
conditions, the researchers say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891216-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MissingChildren 1stLd-Writethru a0516 12-16 1084</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Children, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Vigilant in Neighborhood Where Girl Vanished</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDs: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng: `One false,' to make it trash bin,
sted dumpster; INSERTS 1 graf after 24th graf pvs, bgng: `The
next,' to include that police don't suspect girl's father. Picks up
25th graf, `As for'
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LORTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's after school on a brilliant wintry day,
but there are no children romping in the snow at the Woodside
Apartments where 5{-year-old Melissa Lee Brannen disappeared from a
Christmas party two weeks ago.
   At the school bus stop, where perhaps one mother might have
stood with a dozen children last month, now three or four mothers
wait, says resident Sally Marquis, whose 2{-year-old son Daniel
played with Melissa for hours at the apartment complex party from
which the little girl vanished.
   ``Those who aren't there, you can see them lined up at the
bottom of the stairs,'' keeping an eye on their youngsters from a
distance without embarrassing those who think they're grown up
enough to wait alone, she said.
   The middleclass neighborhood around the modern Woodside complex
is ``tense, scared,'' resident Susan Kunze said.
   ``Usually you see kids out all the time, at all hours, but
lately it's rare that you see a kid out alone without a parent or
at least a friend,'' she said.
   The Kunze children _ Diane, 9, and Joseph, 10 _ know their
quiet, shy little friend Melissa has disappeared. They also had
been taught at school and at home, long before Melissa vanished, to
be wary of strangers and to scream and run if someone tried to grab
them. ``I'd scream and kick him in the shins,'' declared Joseph.
   But when a reporter they'd never met knocked on their apartment
door, the two flung it open with a cheerful, ``Hi!'' They left it
wide open as they raced to get their mother.
   Being wary of strangers is a lesson that takes time to seep in.
   When 10-year-old Rosie Gordon, another Fairfax County resident,
was abducted and killed last July, ``Everyone was shocked that it
could happen,'' says Tammy Brannen, Melissa's 27-year-old mother.
   But people at the Woodside Apartments adjacent to the towering
trees of Fort Belvoir didn't take any special precautions. ``I
don't think we ever associated it with happening to us,'' she said.
   Ms. Brannen, who was divorced 2{ years ago and moved to her
apartment in August 1987, seems numb.
   ``It still doesn't really seem real,'' she whispered during an
interview last week. ``At times, it seems like she's over at my
parents or at school and she's going to walk in the door at any
minute.''
   Fairfax County Police Officer Michael Proffitt said, ``We like
to think that since it doesn't happen that often, that we're
somewhat immune from it ... but then we're shocked back to reality
that no one is immune from something like this.''
   The whole region is alert, he says, reflected by the hundreds of
phone calls from concerned citizens. Unfortunately, very few
represent solid leads.
   Proffitt said Melissa's case has generated far more rumors than
any other case in the county.
   One false rumor broadcast by some radio and television stations
was that Melissa's body had been found in a trash bin.
   Ms. Brannen was angered by that report and by reports that an
apartment complex maintenance man had failed lie-detector tests and
had refused to help police although his wife said he was home late
Dec. 3, immediately washed his clothes and cut out parts of his
shoes with a knife. Later reports said the FBI and police had
searched the man's home and emerged with boxes of possible evidence
and were checking blood stains found in his vehicle.
   ``If people hear that, they'll quit looking for her,'' Ms.
Brannen said.
   Police and hundreds of volunteers have conducted numerous
searches of the area, but they have curtailed those until they get
new leads, Proffitt said.
   Despite the area's middle-class, residential nature, about 30
miles south of Washington, D.C., Fairfax County has had its share
of trouble. In addition to the Rosie Gordon slaying, a third-grader
was raped last year in an elementary school restroom.
   That incident prompted the Fairfax County Public Schools to
institute a comprehensive child-safety program for the children and
staff, said Assistant Superintendent Dolores Bohen. Crisis
counseling teams are routinely sent into schools when needed, she
said.
   There are no solid numbers on how many missing children there
are, as these cases are not always reported and there is no central
clearinghouse for the information.
   Scott Mandel, on loan from the Corpus Cristi, Texas Sheriff's
Office to The Center for Missing and Exploited Children, estimated
that at any point, 1 million to 1.5 million children are missing,
of whom the majority are runaways or so-called throwaways, children
kicked out by their parents. Most return the same day, he said.
   The next largest number are parental abduction cases, involving
50,000 to 300,000 children, he said.
   Police confirmed that Melissa's father, Michael Brannen, a toy
store manager in Garland, Texas, who has not seen the girl in two
years, was in Texas when she disappeared. Police don't think her
disappearance is part of a domestic dispute.
   As for abductions by strangers, he said, the center had heard of
511 cases during its first five years of operation ending Sept. 30.
Of those, 158 children had been returned alive, 112 were located
dead. The rest are still missing.
   Ms. Brannen, a single parent who was working as an accountant
for a defense contractor and part-time for two jewelry stores,
rarely sleeps these days. She's never alone. Family and friends
answer the phone.
   She castigates herself for not being more cautious about Melissa
although she estimates it took only two minutes at most for Melissa
to vanish.
   ``You can say lots of `I should have dones,''' she says. ``I
shouldn't have taken her to the party.''
   ``The not knowing is the toughest part,'' says Mandel. ``...To
get a feel for what it's like, a moment of what they're going
through is when you lose your child in a mall. Those 10 minutes
turn into what some of these parents have gone through for 10
years. ... Those moments of hell that you went through momentarily
is what they're living.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Those with information on Melissa should call Fairfax County
(Va.) Police at 1-703-691-2131 or the National Center for Missing
and Exploited Children at 1-800-843-5678.
</TEXT>
