<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Dothard     12-16 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Dothard,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trooper Shot With Wallace Dies in Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNISTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state trooper wounded in the 1972
assassination attempt on Gov. George C. Wallace died of a
self-inflicted gunshot wound in a hospital where he was being
treated for terminal cancer. He was 58.
   Capt. E.C. Dothard, who served 5{ years as state public safety
director, shot himself Friday night at Anniston's Stringfellow
Hospital, where he was diagnosed earlier in the week as having a
terminal malignancy, trooper Lt. James Hyatt said Saturday.
   Dothard joined the governor's security detail in 1963 during the
first of Wallace's four terms.
   In May 1972, he suffered a grazing gunshot wound to the stomach
when Wallace was shot and paralyzed while campaigning for president
in Laurel, Md. One co-worker said Dothard was ``still barking out
orders while on the ground after being shot.''
   A Secret Service agent also was wounded in the assassination
attempt.
   Wallace issued a statement through longtime aide Elvin Stanton
saying Dothard ``was almost a member of my family.''
   ``He was a very close personal friend and a fine citizen who
gave his entire life to law enforcement,'' said Wallace. ``He
traveled all over the world with me and was injured when I was
shot. My prayers and deepest sympathy go out to his entire family.''
   Wallace's assailant, Arthur Bremer, is serving a 53-year
sentence.
   Seven months after the shooting, Wallace appointed Dothard
director of the Alabama Department of Public Safety. He held the
post until April 1978, when he resigned to return to his hometown
of Anniston. At the time of his death, Dothard was serving as
commander of the Jacksonville trooper district.
   Dothard is survived by his wife, Virginia, and four children.
</TEXT>
