<FIRST>r a AM-Stans-Museum     12-16 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stans-Museum,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Rejects Watergate Figure Maurice Stans' Gift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHAKOPEE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Watergate figure Maurice Stans' offer to
donate his family home and a new museum to the city has been
rejected because officials don't want to be responsible for the
upkeep.
   Stans, the onetime Cabinet secretary who pleaded guilty to minor
campaign violations in the Watergate case but was acquitted of more
serious charges, said he wanted to show young people in towns like
Shakopee that they can make it big outside their small communities.
   He offered to turn over to the city the family home, a small
adjacent park and a museum that he would build.
   Stans was deputy postmaster and budget director under President
Eisenhower and secretary of commerce under President Richard Nixon
as well as chairman of Nixon's campaign finance committee. He was
born in Shakopee in 1908 and lived there until he was 17.
   Stans proposed half the museum be reserved for his memorabilia
and the other half could be used by the city for other artifacts of
Shakopee, a town of 10,000 about 15 miles southwest of Minneapolis.
In return, he wanted the city to promise to maintain and staff the
buildings.
   City Administrator Dennis Kraft said Friday that the City
Council decided it did not want to make that kind of long-term
financial commitment.
   Stans was indicted along with former Attorney General John
Mitchell on 10 counts of perjury and conspiracy involving a
$200,000 contribution from financier Robert Vesco. They were
acquitted by a jury.
   Stans later pleaded guilty in a separate case stemming from
Watergate to five non-willful violations of campaign financing laws
and paid a $5,000 fine.
   Stans has continually held that he ``had absolutely no part in
Watergate.''
   Earlier, at least two members of the Shakopee City Council said
that the trial and the fine would have no bearing on their decision
on whether to accept Stans' gift.
</TEXT>
