<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     12-16 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It won't be bristling with brawn, but
``The Men of Smith College'' calendar will have plenty of academic
appeal, say students at the all-women school.
   ``What we were focusing on was their intellect and not their
body,'' said senior Marie Macri, who thought up the idea as a
fund-raising project for ``The Porcupine Rag,'' an annual humorous
magazine she co-edits.
   The calendar, expected to go on sale in February for $4,
features models from all over campus, including professors,
security guards and a cook.
   ``We were tired of hearing there were no men at Smith College,''
said Caitlin Hamilton, co-editor of the Rag.
   Also featured in the not-yet-completed calendar are Harpo, the
pet poodle of Smith President Mary Maples Dunn, and a shot of a
nude bronze statue.
   Hamilton said the calendar isn't intended to make fun of the
models or as an exercise in reverse sexism. Models had the final
say on the pictures used and a statement attached to the calendar
states its role as a tribute to the men of campus.
   Associate art professor Craig Fulton said he had no qualms about
posing once he discovered the academic focus of the publication.
   ``I think this shows the seriousness of the students at Smith,''
Fulton said Friday. ``Once the body goes, the mind is left. Let's
hope the mind continues.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's hotels are trying to
keep tourists happy by offering a free night for any complaint
about their visit, from too much heat to too little sun, from
hangnails to hangovers.
   The Greater Fort Lauderdale Convention and Visitors Bureau
devised the three-month program, in which 41 hotels are offering
customers a free night if they return for another visit.
   ``Whatever the cause _ a few minutes of rain showers or too many
minutes of sunshine _ we'll make it good,'' said Richard Weaver,
the bureau's president.
   There are a few stings attached: The second trip has to be made
before Dec. 31, 1990; the tourist has to pay for at least two other
nights before getting the free one; and the tourist has to be among
the first 250 to complain at any given hotel. That's how many
vouchers each hotel has agreed to give out.
   ``We want to make sure if someone has a bad experience, we want
to make it better,'' said Nicki Grossman, chairman of the Tourist
Development Council, the bureau's governing board.``When they go
back, we don't want to be bad-mouthed.''
</TEXT>
