<DOCNO> AP891216-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Baker-Europe Bjt   12-16 1139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Europe, Bjt,1,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker's Visit Marks Bold U.S. Foray in East German Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: LEADS with 8 grafs to include analysis slug, change dateline
to Potsdam, move up reference to Baker in St. Martin and include precedent-setting
visit by Shevardnadze. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `When Poland'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POTSDAM, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drive across the bridge past
impassive East German border guards was both without precedent in
American history and a bold but risky venture.
   The quiet motorcade to Potsdam carried Secretary of State James
A. Baker III where no secretary of state had gone before and
committed the Bush administration to a rescue operation for East
Germany as winter approaches.
   In his 65-minute meeting with Hans Modrow, the reformist prime
minister, and a second session in a 19th century church with
Lutheran ministers who helped bring down the old discredited
rulers, Baker heard a tale of a tenuous regime struggling to make
it to multiparty elections in May and fearful of a violent
revolution from the streets.
   Baker, the highest-level U.S. official ever to venture into East
Germany, has plunged a once-cautious Bush administration into the
maelstrom of German politics, the reunification debate and a
uniquely dangerous display of what he calls ``people power.''
   Tuesday's foray, after breakfast with West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and a symbolic visit to the disintegrating Berlin Wall,
topped a busy five-day trip to Europe in which Baker also advanced
a ``new architecture'' for the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
and strengthened U.S. ties to the 12-nation European Community.
   Baker neared the end of his trip Saturday when he joined
President Bush on the Caribbean Island of St. Martin, where Bush
was discussing East-West relations with French President Francois
Mitterrand.
   The accelerating sweep of economic and political change in
Eastern and Central Europe calls for policy adjustments in the
West, especially from the United States, from a Cold War posture of
confrontation.
   The Soviets are adjusting too. On Tuesday, Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze will call on NATO Secretary-General Manfred
Woerner at his Brussels headquarters _ not for negotiations, the
former West German defense minister said.
   When Poland and Hungary first broke away from orthodox
Communism, the Bush administration responded with what leading
congressional Democrats and many analysts considered to be undue
caution _ even timidity.
   Congress forced increases in aid programs and pushed the White
House to respond to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's bold
arms control programs and need for Western technology and economic
advice.
   One of the decisions taken while Baker attended a two-day
meeting of the North Atlantic Council in Brussels was a call for a
logical system of separating sensitive technology from other
material that can safely be exported to the East.
   ``We think it's still important to protect strategic technology,
but we should rationalize the process to the extent that things
that are available to some extent off the shelf are not locked up
in a bureaucratic process _ particularly at this time of
significant reform,'' Baker said Friday at a news conference in
Brussels.
   This time around, as Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria and especially
East Germany shed hard-line leaders and Marxist economics, the Bush
administration is out front with the promise of the same kind of
aid given Poland and Hungary if they keep it up.
   There may even be a special food grant to assist the Modrow
government through the winter and to give it better than a 50-50
chance of surviving to hold the elections scheduled for May.
   The ministers Baker saw on Tuesday told him the next stage in
the East German revolution could be retribution against former
party officials and the military.
   While Baker was in Europe there were more reports of attacks on
security officers and performers who had enjoyed privileges under
the old order. On Tuesday, while Baker was in Berlin and Potsdam,
the novelist Kristof Hein said in an interview with the communist
youth newspapers Junge Welt that East Germans had to guard against
creating ``new injustices.''
   Otherwise, he said, ``in 20 years, we will not only be
commemorating the victims of Stalinism, but we'll also have to
rehabilitate the victims of de-Stalinization.''
   Baker's public statements after seeing Modrow harped on one
theme _ that the political and economic changes must be brought
about peaceably.
   ``It is that, as much as anything else, that represents the
political signal that we desire to send by being here today,'' he
said standing alongside the embattled prime minister in a crowded
hotel driveway.
   The trip to Potsdam, where the allied leaders in World War II
made preparations for dealing with a defeated Germany and a
partitioned Berlin, was not on Baker's schedule when he set out for
Europe last Sunday.
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Barkley is credited with persuading
Baker at a meeting Monday night to go to Potsdam the next day to
show support for the East German government.
   Baker sent a cable to Moscow reassuring the Kremlin the visit
was not intended to be provocative and he crossed the Glienicke
Bridge in a stately motorcade that attracted little attention from
onlookers.
   It was the same bridge the late American U-2 pilot Francis Gary
Powers and celebrated Jewish dissident Natan Scharansky crossed to
the West after being freed from Soviet prisons.
   Baker urged Modrow to press ahead with political reform. He
soft-pedaled the explosive issue of reunification with West
Germany, which has jangled nerves in Poland, the Soviet Union and
France.
   While economic reunification appears inevitable, Baker wants
political union to be gradual.
   In Brussels, Baker urged the NATO allies at the annual winter
foreign ministers meeting to consider the ``new architecture'' for
Europe he had outlined in a speech Tuesday to the Berlin press club.
   The plan is designed to transform the 40-year-old military
alliance as East-West tensions ease into a mixture of political,
economic and military elements.
   The allies liked several of the specific Baker proposals. They
will consider setting up panels to monitor troop reductions in
Europe and taking on the role of referee for regional conflicts.
   Stopping next at the European Commission, Baker won support for
stronger U.S. ties to the European Community as it moves toward
economic integration of Western Europe in 1992.
   On a third front, Baker participated in decisions by a group of
24 nations to commit $6 billion in economic assistance to Poland
and Hungary over the next several years.
   Baker, who had told his partners that `pledges of aid are not
enough,'' was pleased with the overall Western response.
   But, he said Friday night, ``In the final analysis, it is going
to be up to the people of these countries, the people power that
has generated these peaceful revolutions. It is going to be up to
them to determine whether or not it succeeds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
