<FIRST>r a AM-ProtectedWitness     12-16 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Protected Witness,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protected Witness Pleads Guilty to Resisting Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who entered the federal witness
protection program after testifying against a New York City cocaine
ring has pleaded guilty to resisting arrest.
   The man, with the single name of Arjune, entered the guilty plea
Friday under an agreement with county prosecutors. District Judge
Charles Dorn accepted the prosecutors' recommendation that Arjune
be neither jailed nor fined.
   A second misdemeanor charge of failure to obey an officer was
dismissed.
   Arjune, 47, was living in Spokane under the name of Amos Hardeen
when he alleged that he had been beaten and called a racial slur by
a police officer who stopped him Sept. 1 for allegedly speeding.
   Police Chief Terry Mangan rebutted Arjune's claims, saying he
was claiming racial harassment to cover his crimes and had falsely
accused Officer Patricia Madsen. Mangan and Ms. Madsen said Arjune
ran a stop sign and assaulted the officer in front of his house
after she followed him home, although no assault charges were filed
by the prosecutor's office.
   As a result of the dispute, Arjune's identity became public and
he has since been moved to another town.
   Arjune was a key prosecution witness in a major cocaine trial in
New York City. He also testified against two people convicted in
the Feb. 26, 1988, shooting death of Edward Byrne, a rookie police
officer who was guarding Arjune's house at the time.
   The shooting gained national attention last year as a symbol of
the drug problem when Byrne's parents appeared with
then-presidential candidate George Bush and he cited the
policeman's slaying as a reason to support the death penalty.
   Arjune and Ms. Madsen both said they passed lie-detector tests
verifying their accounts of the Sept. 1 incident.
   ``I'm sorry for what happened,'' Arjune said in court Friday.
``As long as I live in this world, I would never hurt a police
officer.''
</TEXT>
