<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     12-16 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Killed As Suspected Collaborator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian patriarchs said Saturday they will
cancel festive holiday visits and limit celebrations in sympathy
with the uprising in the occupied lands, where violence persisted
with the killing of a Palestinian by fellow Arabs.
   The office of the Roman Catholic Patriarch, Michel Sabbah, said
Sabbah met with the Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem, Diodoros
I, and other Christian leaders to discuss the ``deteriorating
situation' in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Sabbah, the first Arab to head the Catholic Church in Jerusalem,
supports Palestinian demands for an independent state.
   The patriarchs decided to issue a Christmas message voicing the
need for justice and peaceful settlement of the conflict; to
restrict Christmas celebrations to liturgical services and prayers
for justice and peace; and to cancel all Christmas visits and other
festivities ``in sympathy with those who mourn their beloved ones.''
   The decision followed Thursday's announcement in the West Bank
town of Bethlehem and neighboring Beit Sahour that Christmas
celebrations would be canceled for the third year in a row to
support the uprising.
   In east Jerusalem's village of Jabel Mukaber, police found the
body of a 46-year-old Palestinian and said he apparently was
murdered because he was a suspected collaborator with Israel.
   The national news agency Itim said the victim, Khalil Kareen,
was stabbed to death inside his home. Kareen was found in a pool of
blood on the floor, his hands tied behind his back and his head
covered with a rag, it said.
   It was the first such killing in Israeli-annexed east Jerusalem,
and it brought to 159 the number of Palestinians murdered by fellow
Arabs on suspicion of being pro-Israeli agents during the two-year
uprising.
   In addition, 631 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli
gunfire and 43 Israelis have died.
</TEXT>
