<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Westbury     12-16 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Westbury,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Actress Marjorie Westbury Dies of Cancer at 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marjorie Westbury, one of Britain's best-known
radio actresses, died of cancer Saturday at the age of 84.
   She was told she had cancer two weeks ago and died at her
farmhouse near Uckfield in Sussex in southern England, her friend
Helen Bohan said.
   Miss Westbury was best known for her 30 years in the role of
Steve, the wife of radio detective Paul Temple in Francis
Durbridge's series on the British Broadcasting Corp
   In the 1950s she won two radio awards as outstanding actress of
the year. Her work was so admired by one fan that she left Miss
Westbury about $42,000 in her will in 1957.
   Born near Birmingham, Miss Westbury won a scholarship to the
Royal College of Music in London and began her professional career
as a singer in 1932, when she sang Gretel at the Old Vic for Lilian
Baylis. She started singing on the radio the following year.
   In 1942, during a rehearsal break with the BBC Midlands Singers,
a producer heard her imitations and offered her her first speaking
part.
   Her last major work for radio was her 50th anniversary play in
1983, when she chose to perform in ``Waters of the Moon,'' choosing
her own cast which included acting friends Mary Wimbush, Patricia
Hayes and Martin Jarvis.
   John Tydeman, head of BBC radio drama, called her a ``highly
accomplished and versatile actress'' and said her voice remained
``pure and perfect throughout her long life.''
   Miss Westbury, who never married, lived alone.
</TEXT>
