<FIRST>r a PM-Mofford-Murderers 2ndLd-Writethru a0503 12-16 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mofford-Murderers, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0503,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corbin Says Commutations Are Void</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to to CORRECT that Mofford is saying her
commutations are void, not that she is asking parole board to reverse her
decision; and recasts for transition. Pickup 4th graf, `Hamm and...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford says she agrees with the state
attorney general's assessment and will tell the state parole board
that her commutations of two murder sentences are void.
   Attorney General Bob Corbin's opinion Friday said the
commutations of James Hamm and Carl Kummerlowe could be considered
void because the parole board that recommended them earlier in the
year did not fully comply with a victim-notification law.
   ``The attorney general's opinion confirms my original belief
that these commutations were flawed and must be considered void,''
Mofford said in a statement.
   Hamm and his wife, prisoner-rights activist Donna Leone Hamm,
would not comment on the ruling. Kummerlowe has refused to comment
in the past and was unavailable because of an alleged disciplinary
lapse that placed him in lock-up.
   Kummerlowe, 62, was sentenced to life for the 1969 killing of a
service-sation manager who was bludgeoned to death, dismembered and
packed into ice chests.
   Hamm, 37, was sentenced to life in prison in 1974 for two
drug-related murders.
   The judge who sentenced Kummerlowe said he should never be
paroled and former Gov. Bruce Babbitt rejected the parole board's
recommendation in 1986 that Kummerlowe's sentence be commuted.
   Both inmates were model prisoners who had rehabilitated
themselves through service to others, the parole board had said.
Mrs. Mofford said she based her decision to commute the sentences
earlier this year on that report.
   Corbin said Friday that there were no Arizona cases detailing a
governor's power to reverse commutations and that courts in other
jurisdictions had split over the issue.
   The victim-notification law requires notification to the
victim's family, prosecutors and a judge before any commutation or
parole hearing, Corbin said, and there is no evidence that the
notifications were sent out to all the necessary parties.
   Board chairman Arter Johnson, a Mofford appointee, did not
return calls immediately.
</TEXT>
