<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-EastTimor     12-16 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-East Timor,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Baker Asked to Probe Reports of Human Rights Abuses in East Timor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One hundred fourteen members of the House
asked the State Department on Saturday to launch an official
inquiry into reports of arrests and torture of demonstrators in
East Timor following Pope John Paul's visit there on Oct. 12.
   In a letter drafted by Rep. Tony P. Hall, D-Ohio, the bipartisan
congressional group asked Secretary of State James A. Baker III to
order the U.S. Embassy in Jakarta to ``investigate the events
surrounding the demonstration and its aftermath'' and to urge the
Indonesian government to allow any detainees to be examined by
doctors selected by their families.
   The letter said as many as 40 people may have been detained
after a demonstration by nationalists who shouted slogans praising
the Pope and demanding independence from Indonesia, which occupied
East Timor in 1975. The former Portuguese colony is predominately
Roman Catholic.
   ``We are concerned about reports that several of those arrested
were tortured to extract `confessions,''' the letter said. ``While
such reports are difficult to verify, they would fall into a
well-established pattern in East Timor and throughout Indonesia of
mistreatment and abuse of detainees in the period immediately
following arrest.''
   State Department spokesman Mark Dillen declined immediate
comment on the request Saturday on grounds that officials had not
yet reviewed the letter.
</TEXT>
