<FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 1544EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MissingPlane     12-16 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Plane,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searchers Looking For Missing Plane That Carried Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A light airplane with six people aboard
disappeared during a snowstorm in eastern New York, and a search
Saturday was hampered by bad weather, authorities said.
   The missing twin-engine Piper Navaho took off Friday afternoon
from Glens Falls Airport, 50 miles north of Albany, bound for
Orange County Airport just north of New York City, said Ann
MacMillan, spokeswoman for the Civil Air Parol. The private plane
was reported about 30 miles south of Albany when it disappeared
between 5:30 p.m. and 6 p.m., she said.
   Blustery weather hit much of New York about the time the plane
took off. As much as 7 inches of snow fell in the northern Catskill
Mountains, where the plane was last reported.
   Planes searching Saturday south of Albany were buffeted by high
winds and blowing snow, MacMillan said. The weather forced the six
rescue planes to call off their search, she said.
   Sightings of low-flying aircraft Friday afternoon were reported
from the Massachusetts border to Utica in central New York, forcing
searchers to look for the plane in a half dozen counties, she said.
   ``We're still plotting courses'' and haven't determined exactly
where the plane might have gone down, she said.
   About 90 state troopers, forest rangers, Army National Guardsmen
and other rescuers were on foot looking for the plane, MacMillan
said.
   Searchers had not picked up the plane's emergency signal, she
said.
   The plane was based at Robbinsville-Trenton airport in New
Jersey. MacMillan said she could not release the names of those
aboard.
</TEXT>
