<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSAutopsies     12-16 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Autopsies,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Considers Autopsy AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical officials say they want AIDS tests
performed during all autopsies as a step to prevent the spread of
the disease, but other state officials say privacy issues must be
considered.
   ``This is a serious disease, a lethal, contagious disease, and
our hands are tied for investigation, reporting, and protecting
those around us,'' said Dr. Pierre Provost, chairman of the state
commission on medical-legal investigation. ``If we treated
syphillis like we treat AIDS, humanity would have been dead a
century ago.''
   Last week, officials in New York City said they plan to test for
acquired immune deficiency syndrome during all autopsies and to use
the results to find out who else might be infected.
   But a leading AIDS activist said the New York program is
``outrageous,'' and he will oppose any such plan in Massachusetts.
   ``The dead person can't tell them who the contacts are, so the
medical examiner's going to speculate about who the guy's
girlfriends or boyfriends are?'' said Larry Kessler, director of
the AIDS Action Committee.
   Kessler said he would not object to anonymous testing during
autopsies for statistical research.
   Mary Ann Hart, a spokesman for the Department of Public Health,
said her agency was not ready to take a position on the issue.
   Tom McNaught, spokesman for state Attorney General James
Shannon, said his office is consulting the Department of Public
Health and the medical-legal investigation commission on the issue.
   Shannon is concerned with the state's AIDS confidentiality
statutes, which require consent from anyone being tested for AIDS,
McNaught said.
</TEXT>
