<FIRST>r a AM-ToyConsultant     12-16 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toy Consultant,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Toys That Teach, Stranger Knows Best</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISE ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents needn't fret about picking out the right
toys for their children. For $300, a toy consultant will do the job.
   Karen Ard, an elementary school teacher, has no trouble buying
toys for her 4-year-old son. She went into the toy consulting
business when she realized it wasn't so simple for others.
   Ard, 36, decided she could share her skills with parents who did
not have the know-how, time, patience or foresight to choose toys
that foster the creative and educational development of their
children.
   Her consulting service, Toys That Teach, serves New Yorkers who
have children 6 years old or under. For each child, Ard prepares an
individually tailored list of toys for parents to buy over the
course of a year.
   She charges $300, plus a 10 percent surcharge on any toys that
she buys.
   ``Many kids don't have related educational toys at all,'' said
Ard.
   Her recommendations fall into seven categories: Art, music,
reading readiness, science, math, social studies and motor skills.
   Ard takes into account age, where a child goes with friends,
what parks they play in, what classes they take and whether they
demonstrate special talents or interests. She considers the
parents' occupations and where the family vacations. An interview
with the parents and a visit to the child's room help shape the
final plan.
   ``All this is just to set a picture for the child,'' said Ard.
   Non-educational toys, Ard thinks, should be left for birthday
parties.
   ``My objective is to balance out the child's scheme in life,''
Ard said.
</TEXT>
