<FIRST>u i AM-BushCold     12-16 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Cold,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Fights Cold, Laryngitis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARIGOT, St. Martin (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush suffered the ills of a
Washington winter during his afternoon visit Saturday with French
President Francois Mitterrand on this tropical island.
   During a 45-minute news conference on the two leaders' talks,
Bush coughed several times and blew his nose into a handkerchief he
pulled from his breast pocket. His voice was raspy due to his cold
and mild laryngitis.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush was feeling
``the normal discomfort'' associated with laryngitis.
   During the flight Bush remained in the front of the plane
reading his briefing books and ``trying to save his voice,''
Fitzwater said.
   He said Bush was taking throat lozenges, a decongestant and
common aspirin.
   Asked if Bush became ill while sitting outdoors at the White
House tree-lighting ceremony, Fitzwater said: ``He cannot pinpoint
when it occurred'' but attrributed it to the general Washington
weather.''
   Bush had two refills of his water glass brought to the podium
and drank rapidly.
   Earlier, Bush was asked how he was feeling as he sat with
Mitterrand in a beachside gazebo.
   ``Better, thank you,'' he said. ``Doesn't hurt.
   ``Just can't talk, which is a great relief for the president of
France.''
   Bush and Mitterrand spent much of the afternoon under the shade
in the 90-degree heat of this French Caribbean island.
   They changed from the business suits to casual wear for a brief
walk along the white, sandy beach, with the waves lapping near
Bush's shoes.
   Mitterrand wore a tunic-type suit, and Bush a white
short-sleeved shirt and khaki trousers.
   Bush said he was enjoying the tropical climate, and the break
from the bone-chilling weather of Washington.
</TEXT>
