<FIRST>r p AM-GOP-ChristianResolutions     12-16 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP-Christian Resolutions,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Rejects Resolutions Promoting Christianity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three resolutions promoting Christianity were
rejected by a committee of the Arizona Republican Party on
Saturday, raising the threat of a floor fight at the GOP's state
convention next month.
   The resolutions were among nine submitted to the party's
resolutions committee in advance of the Jan. 27 convention. All
nine were rejected.
   Republicans from Pinal County south of Phoenix, who drafted a
``Christian nation'' resolution passed at the party's last state
convention, submitted resolutions this year promoting diligent
Bible study, restoration of ``Christian prayer'' in public schools
and recognition of the United States' ``Christian heritage.''
   Anetta Conant, who was representing Pinal County, cast the only
votes in favor of the resolutions, which were rejected by 30-1
votes.
   Ms. Conant said she was not surprised by the defeat. ``I
expected it,'' she said.
   She said she expected all three resolutions to be introduced
from the floor during the state convention, but was not hopeful
they would be passed because many delegates who believed in them
would not have the courage ``to vote their convictions.''
   Pinal County delegates won passage of a resolution declaring the
United States a ``Christian nation'' during last January's state
convention. The measure was introduced from the floor after many
delegates already had left the meeting.
   State Republican Chairman Burton Kruglick, who is Jewish,
engineered passage of another resolution five weeks later,
attacking those who promote ``racism, anti-Semitism or religious
intolerance.''
   Kruglick wrote members of the resolutions committee before
Saturday's meeting, urging rejection of the new resolutions.
   ``The message sent by these three resolutions is one of
exclusion and a clear disregard for those of other than Christian
faith,'' Kruglick wrote.
   Dean Cooley of Phoenix, co-chairman of the resolutions
committee, said steps have been taken to keep surprise resolutions
from being passed at the Jan. 27 state convention.
   ``We have a new rule that a copy of each resolution will have to
be in the hands of each person before a vote is taken,'' he said.
   The resolutions committee also unanimously rejected a measure
supporting ``the constitutional principle of separation of church
and state.''
   Kurt Davis, the state party's executive director, said the
committee decided that issue is dealt with adequately in the
national Republican platform.
   Other resolutions rejected by the committee supported
floridation of water supplies, establishment of a national
presidential primary and protection of employees from mandatory
polygraph tests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
