<FIRST>r a AM-MedalDenied     12-16 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medal Denied,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Veteran Says He's Dissapointed But Won't Let Medal Issue Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MI6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYA L. WESLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A World War II veteran Saturday criticized the
Army's investigation into his claims that he singlehandledly killed
more than 500 Japanese soldiers.
   The Army said it won't give the Medal of Honor to David Rubitsky
because it could not prove his claims.
   ``I'll admit that I am 72 years old and maybe I don't think with
a full head, but when I talked with the investigators, I began to
think that maybe they didn't think with a full head,'' Rubitsky
said.
   Rubitsky said he would continue his fight for the medal, which
he contends he was denied because he is Jewish.
   ``Being Jewish has a lot to do with it,'' he said. ``You have to
be Jewish to understand it.''
   Rubitsky, who lives in Milton 40 miles southwest of Milwaukee,
appeared at a news conference with Joseph Stehling, a retired
brigadier general who has signed an affidavit supporting Rubitsky's
claims.
   Rubitsky claims that he killed up to 600 Japanese in the New
Guinea jungle during a 21-hour siege in early December 1942.
   Stehling signed an affidavit saying he inspected the battle
scene and there were more than 500 Japanese wounded or killed by
Rubitsky's actions.
   ``I saw the dead bodies _ lots of them,'' Stehling said
Saturday. ``I'm frustrated a little bit because they don't believe
me.''
   Retired Gen. Herbert Smith, who died in September, signed a
similar affidavit. Another affidavit in the case, signed by a
military messenger, said a colonel, now dead, had denied Rubitsky
his medal because Rubitsky was Jewish.
   Lt. Col. Terry Adkins, chief of the Army's Military Awards
Branch that made the decision, said Friday the Army could not even
prove fierce fighting occured during the period.
   Adkins said the Army examined scores of documents, including
testimony from Japanese prisoners of war, battle logs and
interviews.
   Rubitsky said the decision implied he, Stehling and Smith, were
liars.
   ``They're not only calling me a liar. These men saw what
happened. They said they saw it; they signed the affidavits,''
Rubitsky said.
   Rubitsky told reporters he has spent $16,000 since he began his
fight for the medal in 1986, including the money he spent to travel
to Washington to present his case.
   ``I wouldn't have spent $16,000 if I was lying about
something,'' he said.
   Rubitsky said he doesn't know if there is an appeal proccess,
but said he intends to pursue the matter.
   Rubitsky said he began seeking the medal in 1986 after a reunion
of the 128th Regiment, when it was learned that he had never been
recommended for the medal.
   ``The medal never entered my mind,'' he said. ``I wanted to
forget the horrible things that happened out there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
