<SECOND>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post-election Violence Leaves One Dead, Dozens Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of the new civilian
president-elect clashed with police after victory celebrations
across the country, leaving one person dead and dozens injured,
authorities said Saturday.
   At least 870 people were reported arrested.
   Police said a woman was killed during demonstrations in Temuco,
540 miles south of Santiago. They gave no details, but the official
Orbe news agency said she was killed ``when demonstrators altered
the public order, damaging public properties, and forced police to
act.''
   Thousands of supporters of opposition leader Patricio Aylwin
took to the streets Friday night to celebrate his victory in the
presidential election the day before and an end to military rule.
Police reported disorders in many cities throughout the country but
said the situation calmed down early Saturday.
   They said 589 demonstrators were arrested in Santiago, where
dozens of people were injured, including 20 police officers hit by
rocks. Police arrested 281 people in the resort city of Vina del
Mar, according to officials.
   The violence broke out in Santiago when police started
dispersing people who tried to march in off-limit areas, including
streets next to the presidential palace and Defense Ministry.
Police charged the crowds after some demonstrators began throwing
rocks at them and also at traffic signals and public buses.
   Police had used water cannons and tear gas Thursday to scatter
more than 100 demonstrators in Santiago who were demanding the
immediate release of imprisoned leftists, including some accused of
terrorism and guerrilla activities.
   Aylwin, a 71-year-old Christian Democrat, was the candidate of a
17-party center-left coalition and won Thursday's presidential
election with 55.2 percent of the vote. Hernan Buchi, 40, the
candidate backed by the military regime, received 29.4 percent with
the remainder divided among minor candidates.
   Aylwin is scheduled to take office March 11, succeeding Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, the army commander who has been president since
leading the coup that ousted the government of Marxist President
Salvador Allende in September 1973. Pinochet, a hard-line rightist,
had said he will remain as army commander after the military turns
over power to the new elected government.
</TEXT>
