<FIRST>u i AM-Comoros 1stLd-Writethru a0520 12-16 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comoros, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interim Government Calls for Elections in Comoro Islands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to CORRECT that about 40 mercenaries flown
out Thursday and Friday. Also others, but not Denard, left South Africa
on Saturday night. Pickup 7th graf pvs `The soldiers of fortune...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORONI, Comoro Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's new interim leader
says an election will be held in January to replace the president
who was assassinated three weeks ago as European mercenaries took
control of the islands.
   The announcement came Friday, the day after about 40 mercenaries
relinquished control of the country to French troops.
   Said Mohamed Djohar, the new interim leader, invited six
opposition parties, including the opposition Democratic Front, to
take part in a ``free and democratic'' presidential election.
Djohar said the election should be held in mid-January under the
supervision of international observers.
   French soldier of fortune Bob Denard and the other European
mercenaries left the islands Thursday and Friday, with some flying
from Moroni to Paris and some to Johannesburg, South Africa.
   France, the former colonial power, sent 200 troops to the
islands after Djohar requested military assistance under a mutual
defense treaty to restore the country's security. South Africa is
involved because it has a major financial interest in the islands
off southeastern Africa.
   South African and French officials were reported to be trying to
find a final destination for the mercenaries. A spokesman for the
South African government said the mercenaries ``should leave as
soon as possible.''
   The exact number of Mercenaries who were in the islands was
uncertain. South African government sources said there were about
45.
   The sources said more than 20 mercenaries and 17 family members,
including Denard's Comoran wife and their two children, left the
islands Thursday night on a flight to Paris.
   Denard and the 21 remaining mercenaries were flown to South
Africa on Friday.
   The independent South African Press Association reported that 18
of the 22 mercenaries who came to South Africa left the country by
plane Saturday night. It reported that an unidentified spokeswoman
for the Department of Foreign Affairs confirmed the 18 had departed
but did not give their destination. She said Denard was not among
the 18.
   A South African Airways flight left Johannesburg for Paris on
Saturday night, and it was believed the 18 French mercenaries were
aboard.
   South Africa wants Denard to leave, the government sources said,
but he is still negotiating with authorities in France, where he
faces legal charges stemming from his involvement in a failed coup
attempt in the West African country of Benin in 1977.
   The soldiers of fortune, who led and trained the Comoran
Presidential Guard, had disarmed the regular army and effectively
controlled the islands since President Ahmed Abdallah was
assassinated Nov. 26.
   Most Comorans believe Denard or his men carried out the killing.
Denard has claimed he was in the room when Abdallah, whom he
brought to power in a 1978 coup, was shot accidentally by a
bodyguard.
   Denard _ who had taken out Comoran citizenship, married a local
woman and acquired substantial real estate and business interests _
was seen arguing with Abdallah before the assassination. Denard
also is believed to have played a role in an attempt to overthrow
the president of Benin more than a decade ago.
   All was reported calm on the Comoros on Saturday, and two of the
four French warships that had taken up positions near the islands
on Friday withdrew to the French-administered island of Mayotte.
   The 50 French troops remaining in the Comoro Republic took
control of stocks of munitions formerly belonging to the
Presidential Guard. Djohar has asked the soldiers to reorganize the
Comoran military, until now split between the elite Presidential
Guard and the poorly trained and equipped regular army.
   The transfer of control from the Presidential Guard to the
French forces at Moroni airport ended several weeks of efforts by
France and South Africa to dislodge Denard and his men.
   Both French and South African officials stressed that none of
the mercenaries had been paid ``one cent'' in exchange for their
departure. Denard had reportedly requested millions of dollars as
the price of his leaving.
   The Comoro Republic is made up of three islands off Africa. A
fourth island in the archipelago, Mayotte, remains French. Most of
the 450,000 African, Arab and Malay residents are subsistence
farmers with annual incomes of about $300.
   In another development Saturday, a Comoran politician accused of
leading a failed 1985 coup was released from jail.
   Authorities freed Moustoifa Said Cheikh, leader of the
opposition Democratic Front, who had been sentenced to life
imprisonment for the November 1985 coup that failed to topple
Abdallah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
