<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle     12-16 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Will Delay Space Shuttle Launch Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The liftoff of space shuttle
Columbia scheduled for Thursday will be delayed again because of
lagging work at the launch pad, sources said Saturday.
   The mission to launch and retrieve a satellite has already been
postponed twice. No new date will be set until shuttle managers
meet Monday, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has not
officially changed the liftoff set for 6:04 p.m. Thursday.
   The new date could be Friday or Saturday. But NASA has said that
if it can't launch by Saturday, it would delay the effort until at
least Dec. 27 to free workers for the Christmas holiday.
   The sources said there is a possibility the flight could be put
off until New Year's Day to give workers a longer holiday and to
permit an annual electrical inspection of space center facilities
planned during the last week of each year.
   The launch had been scheduled for this Monday, but last
Wednesday NASA postponed it by two days. On Friday, it delayed the
launch another day.
   The delays have been caused by unfinished work on launch pad
39A, which hasn't been used for a shuttle launch in nearly four
years. A two-year, $50 million refurbishment of the complex was
recently completed, and technicians have not finished checking
several systems, such as ground lines that carry fuel to the
shuttle.
   Some tiny fuel leaks and other minor problems have turned up,
slowing work.
   A new mobile launch platform is being used for the first time,
and checking some of its systems has taken longer than anticipated.
   During 10 days in space, Columbia's five astronauts are to
release a communications satellite for the Navy, then track down
and retrieve a large science satellite that has been orbiting Earth
for six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
