<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Kohl     12-16 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Kohl,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Praises Hungary for Leading Role in East European Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visiting Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West
Germany praised Hungary on Saturday for leading the reforms
sweeping Eastern Europe and said it ``knocked the first stone'' out
of the Berlin Wall.
   Kohl, who arrived earlier in the day for an official three-day
visit, thanked Hungary as he received an honorary doctorate at
Eoetvoes Lorand University.
   ``Hungary knocked the first stone from the Wall,'' Kohl said,
referring to the decision to open Hungarian borders with Austria on
Sept. 11.
   The exodus of tens of thousands of East Germans to West Germany
via Hungary and Austria helped spark unprecedented political
reforms in the ruling Communist parties of East Germany and other
Soviet-bloc countries.
   Kohl said that without the ``courageous decision by the
Hungarian government,'' the dramatic changes in East Germany would
not have happened _ at least not so quickly.
   ``The solidarity and help of the Hungarians for the people who
were longing for freedom will not be forgotten,'' Kohl told the
university audience.
   He promised additional West German financial aid to help Hungary
restructure its economy and society.
   Kohl's government has set aside for Hungary state-guaranteed
credits worth millions of dollars.
   Kohl was welcomed at the airport by Hungarian Premier Miklos
Nemeth. The two held talks Saturday afternoon, and Kohl will
address Parliament on Monday.
