<FIRST>r a AM-SplitLiver     12-16 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Split Liver,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transplant Patient Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2-year-old boy who received a split liver in
a transplant last week died Saturday, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Mitchell Wallace of Hannibal, N.Y., died of multiple systems
failure about 12:20 p.m., said Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh
spokeswoman Margie Buczynski.
   Doctors plan to perform tests to determine what caused the
failure, she said.
   A lack of available donor organs led Pittsburgh doctors to split
one liver for transplant into Mitchell and a 3-year-old child
Wednesday.
   The hospital did not identify or release other details about the
other child at the request of parents.
   The 3-year-old has been taken out of the hospital's intensive
care unit and was in serious condition late Saturday, Ms. Buczynski
said.
   Wednesday's surgery was the hospital's second attempt at
transplanting a liver into two young patients. Mitchell received
his first split liver Nov. 29 at Children's Hospital.
   Dr. Robert Gordon, a transplant surgeon at University of
Pittsburgh hospitals, said last week that Mitchell's first
transplanted liver had not been functioning properly.
   Before the operations, Mitchell had suffered from liver failure
of unknown origin. After his own liver was removed, he was found to
have hepatitis.
