<FIRST>r a AM-SouthernCalXmas     12-16 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Cal Xmas,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Throng of Kids and Moms Get Big Christmas Party on Skid Row</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Claus floated over Skid Row in a
hot-air balloon Saturday to the cheers of a throng of poor children
as a downtown mission gave away thousands of toys, trees and food
to celebrate the Christmas season.
   Several streets around the Fred Jordan Mission were closed to
traffic and were filled with children and their parents, mostly
only mothers, as volunteers placed toys and food into sacks to give
away as presents.
   For most of the families it would be the only Christmas
celebration, said Tom Jordan, son of the late founder of the
mission.
   ``I believe that well over 90 percent would not have anything
out of the ordinary if it wasn't for this Christmas party,'' he
said.
   Jordan estimated that between 15,000 and 25,000 homeless or
needy children and their families would take part by the end of the
day.
   The mission had more than 40,000 toys, 25,000 sacks containing
fixings for chicken dinners, 8,000 Christmas trees and 8,000
blankets to give away.
   Individuals and companies donated the goods, said Mary Ann
Milhous, who with her husband, Paul, helped plan the party and
marshal 500 volunteers.
   ``I think the motivation is the children,'' said Mrs. Milhous.
``There are more (poor) women and children now.
   ``I think it's the Christmas spirit,'' she said. ``It makes
Christmas Christmas.''
   The fun included musical entertainment and Santa bobbing
overhead beneath a tethered hot air balloon.
   The mission, which has been serving poor people since 1944,
provides 1,000 meals a day, gives 250 people beds each night and
offers programs for children and rehabilitation for drug and
alcohol abusers.
   The holiday spirit was present elsewhere in Southern California
as well.
   Actress Betty White led a group of entertainers on a visit to
Rancho Los Amigos hospital in Downey for an all-day spree of
gift-giving, wheelchair races and visits by Santa Claus to patients.
   The Academy of Television Arts and Sciences has organized visits
by stars to Rancho Los Amigos for 20 years. This year the
celebrities brought $25,000 worth of donated gifts.
