<FIRST>r a AM-HollywoodAuction     12-16 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hollywood Auction,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hollywood Memorabilia Auction Brings $1.1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A celluloid from ``Fantasia'' depicting Mickey
Mouse as a sorcerer's apprentice and others of Peter Pan and Bambi
were among the top sellers Saturday at an auction at Sotheby's.
   The Mickey Mouse celluloid from the 1940 Walt Disney film sold
for $22,000, said Julia Zagrodnik, a Sotheby's spokeswoman.
   The celluloid of Peter Pan, from the 1953 Disney film of the
same name, sold for $17,600, she said.
   Saturday's top seller was a 1900 French musical puppet, ``The
Drunkard,'' that nods its head and sways as it tries to lift a
bottle to its lips. It sold for $23,100, Zagrodnik said.
   The auction marked the second day of the ``Collectors
Carrousel'' sale that included dolls and toys as well as Hollywood
memorabilia. The two days brought in a total of $1.1 million,
Zagrodnik said.
   An oil painting by Batman creator Bob Kane of the Caped Crusader
atop a building with skyscrapers in the background, circa 1945,
sold for $13,200, she said.
   A Bambi celluloid from the 1942 Walt Disney movie ``Bambi'' sold
for $11,000, she said.
   In another auction Saturday, Christie's sold art and furnishings
that appeared in Paramount and RKO films for a total of $1.6
million.
   The top sellers included a circa 1900 Baroque-style giltwood and
painted grand piano that was used in the Paramount films ``Death
Takes a Holiday'' (1934) and ``Sunset Boulevard'' (1950), as well
as in an episode of the television series ``Star Trek.'' The piano
sold for $60,500.
   A pair of Italian Rococo burl-walnut commodes from the mid-18th
Century, which appeared in the films ``Slightly Scarlet'' (1956)
and ``Susan Slept Here'' (1954), sold for $275,000, Christie's said.
