<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Rebels Kill Mayor, Seven Others in Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels killed a mayor and
seven bodyguards in an ambush in northern Cagayan province, the
military reported Saturday.
   It said insurgents of the communist New People's Army are
stepping up their attacks following the unsuccessful coup attempt
by some military units earlier this month.
   A military report said the ambush occurred Friday on a highway
about 220 miles north of Manila and the rebels killed Tuao Mayor
Roberto Guimbuayan, four policeman and three civilan bodyguards. It
said the killers escaped.
   Gen. Renato de Villa, the chief of staff, said the communist
guerrillas were taking advantage of confusion within the armed
forces since military mutineers launched assaults Dec. 1 trying to
overthrow the government of President Corazon Aquino.
   He said communist guerrillas have made 17 attacks this month. He
gave no casualty figures, but other reports indicate at least 23
people were killed in the guerrilla assaults.
   At least 113 people were killed and more than 500 wounded in
violence related to the military revolt that collapsed Dec. 9 when
the last mutineers gave up.
   The armed forces said at least 3,000 military personnel took
part in the coup attempt and more than half have been taken into
custody by loyal forces. The armed forces have about 160,000
members.
   Rumors persist of renegade troops trying to renew the uprising.
   De Villa told reporters about 500 marines were airlifted Friday
to Davao City, 550 miles southeast of Manila, where there were
report of rebel troopers planning new attacks. But he added:
   ``The coup is finished, and we are just making sure that the
situation does not deteriorate.''
