<FIRST>r a AM-Marilyn'sBed     12-16 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marilyn's Bed,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jersey Antique Dealer Auctions Monroe's Bed To Japanese Buyer</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   HO-HO-KUS, N.J. (AP) _ A Japanese furniture manufacturer paid
$60,300 in a sealed-bid auction Saturday for the nuptial bed of
Marilyn Monroe and Joe DiMaggio, the seller said.
   Hiromi Okawa, chairman of the Oliver America High Point
Woodworking Co. of High Point, N.C., was the lone bidder, said June
Regal, owner of Regal Antiques in this northern New Jersey
community.
   Okawa said he heard of the auction while listening to the radio
in Japan. ``I feel very fortunate to have won this bid,'' he wrote
in a letter to Regal.
   Regal held an auction featuring 30 items from a Beverly Hills
rental house that Monroe and the New York Yankees slugger shared
for the eight months they were married in 1954.
   ``Marilyn Monroe has a special mystique for people all over the
world and our company is very pleased to be able to share memories
of Marilyn Monroe with everyone,'' Okawa said.
   Regal had set a minimum bid of $25,000 for the 19th-century,
four-post oak bed. She said Okawa's company manufactures oak copies
of Early American furniture, a style that is becoming very popular
in Japan.
   Regal said she had expected an avalanche of bids for the bed and
was amazed at the tepid response.
</TEXT>
