<FIRST>r a AM-Soviets-StarWars     12-16 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviets-Star Wars,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Scientists in California to Tour `Star Wars' Research Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN CLEMENTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Soviet scientists were in
California on Saturday to inspect a ``Star Wars'' research
laboratory where a laser is being tested as a weapon for use
against missiles and satellites.
   The focus of the visit to the TRW Capistrano Test Site was the
Alpha chemical laser for Zenith Star, a Strategic Defense
Initiative project the Pentagon hopes will show that a space-based
laser is viable.
   The Soviet delegation arrived at El Toro Marine Corps Air
Station on Friday, accompanied by David Smith, the U.S. ambassador
to the nuclear and space talks in Geneva.
   Yuri Nazarkin, the Soviet ambassador to the talks, led the
Soviet delegation.
   ``We regard our visit to American laboratories as a
confidence-building measure,'' Nazarkin told reporters at the
Marine airfield.
   Smith said results of the trip would show up in Geneva in six
months.
   According to the Air Force, nothing was declassified for the
visit.
   The tour of U.S. facilities doing SDI research stemmed from a
meeting between Secretary of State James Baker and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze in Wyoming last September.
   A group of U.S. officials visited two laboratories in the Soviet
Union last summer.
   The Soviets plan to spend Sunday in California, then travel to
New Mexico to inspect SDI particle-beam research at Los Alamos
National Laboratory on Monday and Tuesday before traveling to
Washington, D.C., for meetings.
</TEXT>
