<FIRST>r a AM-ZsaZsaMovie     12-16 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zsa Zsa Movie,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Sheik to Bankroll Film Featuring Zsa Zsa Gabor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A producer hoping to capitalize on Zsa
Zsa Gabor's police-slapping exploits said Saturday he has cast the
former Hungarian beauty queen to play the mother of Saudi Arabia's
founder in a $50 million film epic.
   The film will chronicle Saudi Arabia from the time of King
Abdel-Aziz ibn Saud, who united the desert kingdom in 1932, to the
present, said Chris Christianson, president of A Major Motion
Picture Co.
   Christianson said Mohammed al-Fassi, an oil-rich Saudi sheik,
agreed recently to bankroll the film, which is scheduled to begin
production in January.
   Al-Fassi made headlines in the early 1980s for a spate of
controversies linked to his enormous wealth and jet-set lifestyle.
   In 1987, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected al-Fassi's appeal of a
more than $77 million divorce settlement. Two years earlier,
al-Fassi's former neighbors in Beverly Hills hoisted glasses of
champagne as a demolition crew leveled a the sheik's fire-ravaged
mansion, which had featured flesh-tone nude statues with
red-painted genitalia.
   Dozens of cats now roam outside al-Fassi's Miami Beach mansion
following his recent decision to set aside $2.5 million to save the
nation's stray felines.
   Mrs. Gabor was scheduled to appear with the sheik at his $3.2
million bayside mansion to announce the film, but she canceled when
her luggage was lost during a flight from Los Angeles, Christianson
said.
   ``She just can't go out to K mart and pick up a dress,''
Christianson said. ``Off-the-rack is just not her.''
   Mrs. Gabor was convicted Sept. 29 of misdemeanor charges for
slapping a Beverly Hills policeman after he pulled over her
Rolls-Royce. She has been sentenced to 72 hours in jail and fines
totaling $2,937, pending an appeal.
   Mrs. Gabor did not return telephone calls Saturday to her room
at The Polo Club in Wellington, about 60 miles north of Miami.
   Christianson, who described the film as ``an epic in the
tradition of Lawrence of Arabia,'' said publicity from Mrs. Gabor's
trial contributed to the casting decision.
   ``Certainly, she's hot right now,'' he said. ``She's an unusual
lady. There's a certain character and flamboyance in all the Gabor
sisters.''
   The role would be a departure for Mrs. Gabor, whose previous
screen appearances were in B movies like ``Queen of Outer Space''
and ``Picture Mommy Dead.''
   Al-Fassi said he wants to educate Western viewers about his
native land and push for democratic reforms there, similar to those
in Eastern Europe.
   ``We do not have a democracy in Saudi Arabia and there are many
problems. We want to instruct people about the royal family and
what they've done to the country,'' al-Fassi said.
   The film, tentatively titled ``A Whisper in the Wind,'' could be
ready for distribution by the end of 1990, Christianson said.
</TEXT>
