<FIRST>r a AM-OfficerKilled     12-16 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Officer Killed,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoplifting Suspect Accused of Killing Officer Remains Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of shootng a policeman to
death at a department store, commandeering a car and fleeing this
quiet farming community remained at large Saturday, the police
chief said.
   Officer Michael Hogan, 43, was killed by a single shot to the
head while interviewing a shoptlifting suspect Friday night.
   A second-degree murder complaint was filed Saturday against
Phillip Lewis Cole, 29, of Minneapolis, Steve Madson, chief of the
16-officer department, said at a news conference.
   Hogan, a 16-year veteran of the force, was called to the store
at 7:15 p.m. by a clerk who had detected a ``fraudulent scheme,''
Madson said. Merchandise that may have been stolen from the store
was being returned for cash, the chief said.
   While interviewing a man police identified as Cole in a private
office of the store, the officer was shot, Madson said, adding the
attack was witnessed by a store employee.
   The gunman ran from the store and ordered two motorists to drive
him to the Minneapolis-St. Paul area, about 60 miles east of this
farming community of 10,000.
   The motorists weren't hurt, Madson said.
   Two women and a man who were arrested Saturday had ties to the
suspect, police said, but Madson declined to elaborate on that. The
three were being held pending possible charges, Madson said.
   Hogan was married and had three children. He was described as a
conscientious, well-liked officer and a lifelong Hutchinson
resident.
</TEXT>
