<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Carter     12-16 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Carter,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Praises Nicaraguan Election Preparations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter met with
President Daniel Ortega on Saturday and praised the work of the
national council in charge of Nicaragua's elections set for Feb. 25.
   ``The Supreme Electoral Council is doing an excellent job, and
they deserve and need all the support of the different political
parties,'' Carter told a news conference.
   He heads a delegation invited by both the leftist Sandinista
government and the opposition to observe preparations for the
election of a president, national assembly and municipal officials.
   Carter said Mariano Fiallos, the electoral council president,
would issue an order this weekend designed to avoid the violence
that occurred during a Dec. 10 opposition rally in the town of
Masatepe, 30 miles southeast of Managua. One person was killed, and
20 were injured.
   Most political parties are aware of the planned order, he said,
but he gave no details and there was no announcement from the
council.
   ``Even if they (the political parties) do not agree with it,
they are going to have to abide by it, because it is an official
order that has the force of law,'' Carter added.
   The Sandinistas and leaders of the United National Opposition
have accused each other of provoking the Masatepe clashes, the most
violent in the two-month-old election campaign.
   Agustin Jarquin, head of the opposition Democratic Party of
National Confidence, criticized Carter's support of the council. He
said Carter is naive in believing the council president is
independent of the left-wing government.
   Ortega said he told Carter that he shared his concern about the
violence in Masatepe.
   Carter arrived Wednesday accompanied by his wife Rosalynn;
former Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash.; and former Costa Rican President
Daniel Oduber. They left Saturday for Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
